{"title_page": "Victor Steinbrueck", "text_new": "{{No footnotes|date=May 2008}}\n{{Infobox architect\n| name                  = Victor Eugene Steinbrueck\n| image                 = Victor Steinbrueck.jpg\n| birth_date            = {{Birth date|1911|12|15}}\n| birth_place           = [[Mandan, North Dakota]]\n| death_date            = {{Death date and age|1985|02|14|1911|12|15}}\n| alma_mater            = [[University of Washington College of Architecture and Urban Planning|University of Washington College of Architecture]]\n| practice              = private, [[John Graham, Jr. (architect)|John Graham & Company]]\n| significant_buildings = [[Space Needle]]\n| significant_projects  = [[Pioneer Square, Seattle|Pioneer Square]] and [[Pike Place Market]] preservation\n| awards                = [[American Institute of Architects]] [[FAIA|Fellow]]\n}}\n\n'''Victor Eugene Steinbrueck''' (December 15, 1911 - February 14, 1985) was a [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle]] [[architect]] and [[University of Washington]] faculty member.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pcad.lib.washington.edu/person/2166/|title=PCAD - Victor Eugene Steinbrueck|website=pcad.lib.washington.edu|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> Steinbrueck is best known for his efforts to preserve the city's [[Pioneer Square, Seattle|Pioneer Square]] and [[Pike Place Market]].\n\n==Biography==\nSteinbrueck was born in [[Mandan, North Dakota]], and came to Seattle in 1913.  In 1930 he enrolled in the [[University of Washington College of Architecture and Urban Planning|University of Washington Program in Architecture]], graduating in 1935 with a Bachelor of Architecture ([[B.Arch.]]).  In this period he also worked in the [[Civilian Conservation Corps]].  After apprenticing in a number of private Seattle firms and serving in the military during [[World War II]], he joined the [[University of Washington College of Architecture and Urban Planning|Faculty of Architecture at the University of Washington]] in 1946.  He also initiated his own practice and, over the next two decades, designed a series of regional-modernist residences, built with indigenous materials suited to the climate.\n\nSteinbrueck's focus on the character of Seattle's architecture and urban places dates from the early 1950s when he authored ''A Guide to Seattle Architecture'', published for  [[American Institute of Architects]] national convention held in Seattle in 1953.  Steinbrueck went on to publish several other books promoting awareness of the unique character of [[Seattle]]:  ''Seattle Cityscape'' (1962; published to coincide with [[Century 21 Exposition|Century 21]], the Seattle World's Fair)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ochsner|first=Jeffrey Karl|date=2008|title=Victor Steinbrueck Finds His Voice: From the \"Argus to Seattle Cityscape\"|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/40492217|journal=The Pacific Northwest Quarterly|volume=99|issue=3|pages=122\u2013133|issn=0030-8803}}</ref>, ''Market Sketchbook'' (1968), and ''Seattle Cityscape #2'' (1973).\n\nIn the 1960s Steinbruck became active in [[historic preservation]], and, with others, successfully fought developers' plans to obliterate Seattle's most significant historic district.  He was instrumental in the creation of Seattle's first two historic districts, [[Pioneer Square, Seattle|Pioneer Square]] (1970) and [[Pike Place Market]] (1971).   His own projects were guided by a strong sense of public spirit and social consciousness:  low-income housing, the inclusion of social services, and a number of city parks co-designed with [[landscape architect]] [[Richard Haag]], including the one that now bears his name.\n\nWorking as a consultant to [[John Graham, Jr. (architect)|John Graham & Company]], Steinbrueck played a key role in the design work of the [[Space Needle]] contributing the hour glass shape of the support structure.  In 1963, Steinbrueck was elected a [[FAIA|Fellow]] in the [[American Institute of Architects]].\n\n==Publications==\n* Steinbrueck, Victor, ''A Guide to Seattle Architecture, 1850-1953'', Reinhold Publishing Co., New York 1953.\n* Steinbrueck, Victor, ''Seattle Cityscape'', [[University of Washington Press]], Seattle 1962\n* Steinbrueck, Victor, ''Market Sketchbook'', [[University of Washington Press]], Seattle 1968\n* Steinbrueck, Victor, ''Seattle Cityscape #2'', [[University of Washington Press]], Seattle and London 1973\n* Steinbrueck, Victor, and Nyberg, Folke, ''A Visual Inventory of Buildings and Urban Design Resources for Seattle, Washington'', Historic Seattle Preservation and Development Authority, Seattle 1975-77. Available from [https://web.archive.org/web/20110928024503/http://www.historicseattle.org/resources/neighborhoodinventories.aspx Historic Seattle]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Victor Steinbrueck Park]] (Seattle)\n\n== Read More ==\n* Veith, Thomas, \"Victor Steinbrueck,\" in ''Shaping Seattle Architecture:  A Historical Guide to the Architects'' (Jeffrey Karl Ochsner, ed.), [[University of Washington Press]], Seattle and London, 1994, pages 276-281\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.historylink.org/essays/output.cfm?file_id=67 Steinbrueck, Victor Eugene (1911-1985)] at HistoryLink.org\n*[http://www.historylink.org/essays/output.cfm?file_id=2126 Victor Steinbrueck, Life & Ideas]\n*[http://digitalcollections.lib.washington.edu/cdm/search/collection/dearmassar/searchterm/Victor%20Steinbrueck/field/archit/mode/all/conn/and/cosuppress/ Photographs of Victor Steinbrueck's works from the Phyllis and Robert Massar Photograph Collection of Pacific Northwest Architecture] - University of Washington Digital Collection\n{{Pike Place Market}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Steinbrueck, Victor}}\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:1985 deaths]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Institute of Architects]]\n[[Category:Modernist architects from the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Mandan, North Dakota]]\n[[Category:University of Washington College of Built Environments alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Washington faculty]]\n[[Category:Writers from Seattle]]\n[[Category:Pike Place Market]]\n[[Category:Architects from Seattle]]\n[[Category:Preservationist architects]]\n[[Category:20th-century American architects]]\n[[Category:20th-century historians]]\n", "text_old": "{{No footnotes|date=May 2008}}\n{{Infobox architect\n| name                  = Victor Eugene Steinbrueck\n| image                 = Victor Steinbrueck.jpg\n| birth_date            = {{Birth date|1911|12|15}}\n| birth_place           = [[Mandan, North Dakota]]\n| death_date            = {{Death date and age|1985|02|14|1911|12|15}}\n| alma_mater            = [[University of Washington College of Architecture and Urban Planning|University of Washington College of Architecture]]\n| practice              = private, [[John Graham, Jr. (architect)|John Graham & Company]]\n| significant_buildings = [[Space Needle]]\n| significant_projects  = [[Pioneer Square, Seattle|Pioneer Square]] and [[Pike Place Market]] preservation\n| awards                = [[American Institute of Architects]] [[FAIA|Fellow]]\n}}\n\n'''Victor Eugene Steinbrueck''' (December 15, 1911 - February 14, 1985) was a [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle]] [[architect]] and [[University of Washington]] faculty member.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pcad.lib.washington.edu/person/2166/|title=PCAD - Victor Eugene Steinbrueck|website=pcad.lib.washington.edu|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> Steinbrueck is best known for his efforts to preserve the city's [[Pioneer Square, Seattle|Pioneer Square]] and [[Pike Place Market]].\n\n==Biography==\nSteinbrueck was born in [[Mandan, North Dakota]], and came to Seattle in 1913.  In 1930 he enrolled in the [[University of Washington College of Architecture and Urban Planning|University of Washington Program in Architecture]], graduating in 1935 with a Bachelor of Architecture ([[B.Arch.]]).  In this period he also worked in the [[Civilian Conservation Corps]].  After apprenticing in a number of private Seattle firms and serving in the military during [[World War II]], he joined the [[University of Washington College of Architecture and Urban Planning|Faculty of Architecture at the University of Washington]] in 1946.  He also initiated his own practice and, over the next two decades, designed a series of regional-modernist residences, built with indigenous materials suited to the climate.\n\nSteinbrueck's focus on the character of Seattle's architecture and urban places dates from the early 1950s when he authored ''A Guide to Seattle Architecture'', published for  [[American Institute of Architects]] national convention held in Seattle in 1953.  Steinbrueck went on to publish several other books promoting awareness of the unique character of [[Seattle]]:  ''Seattle Cityscape'' (1962; published to coincide with [[Century 21 Exposition|Century 21]], the Seattle World's Fair), ''Market Sketchbook'' (1968), and ''Seattle Cityscape #2'' (1973).\n\nIn the 1960s Steinbruck became active in [[historic preservation]], and, with others, successfully fought developers' plans to obliterate Seattle's most significant historic district.  He was instrumental in the creation of Seattle's first two historic districts, [[Pioneer Square, Seattle|Pioneer Square]] (1970) and [[Pike Place Market]] (1971).   His own projects were guided by a strong sense of public spirit and social consciousness:  low-income housing, the inclusion of social services, and a number of city parks co-designed with [[landscape architect]] [[Richard Haag]], including the one that now bears his name.\n\nWorking as a consultant to [[John Graham, Jr. (architect)|John Graham & Company]], Steinbrueck played a key role in the design work of the [[Space Needle]] contributing the hour glass shape of the support structure.  In 1963, Steinbrueck was elected a [[FAIA|Fellow]] in the [[American Institute of Architects]].\n\n==Publications==\n* Steinbrueck, Victor, ''A Guide to Seattle Architecture, 1850-1953'', Reinhold Publishing Co., New York 1953.\n* Steinbrueck, Victor, ''Seattle Cityscape'', [[University of Washington Press]], Seattle 1962\n* Steinbrueck, Victor, ''Market Sketchbook'', [[University of Washington Press]], Seattle 1968\n* Steinbrueck, Victor, ''Seattle Cityscape #2'', [[University of Washington Press]], Seattle and London 1973\n* Steinbrueck, Victor, and Nyberg, Folke, ''A Visual Inventory of Buildings and Urban Design Resources for Seattle, Washington'', Historic Seattle Preservation and Development Authority, Seattle 1975-77. Available from [https://web.archive.org/web/20110928024503/http://www.historicseattle.org/resources/neighborhoodinventories.aspx Historic Seattle]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Victor Steinbrueck Park]] (Seattle)\n\n== Read More ==\n* Veith, Thomas, \"Victor Steinbrueck,\" in ''Shaping Seattle Architecture:  A Historical Guide to the Architects'' (Jeffrey Karl Ochsner, ed.), [[University of Washington Press]], Seattle and London, 1994, pages 276-281\n* Ochsner, Jeffrey Karl, \"Victor Steinbrueck Finds His Voice: From the ''Argus'' to ''Seattle Cityscape'',\"  ''Pacific Northwest Quarterly'' 99/3 (Summer 2008),  pages 122-133.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.historylink.org/essays/output.cfm?file_id=67 Steinbrueck, Victor Eugene (1911-1985)] at HistoryLink.org\n*[http://www.historylink.org/essays/output.cfm?file_id=2126 Victor Steinbrueck, Life & Ideas]\n*[http://digitalcollections.lib.washington.edu/cdm/search/collection/dearmassar/searchterm/Victor%20Steinbrueck/field/archit/mode/all/conn/and/cosuppress/ Photographs of Victor Steinbrueck's works from the Phyllis and Robert Massar Photograph Collection of Pacific Northwest Architecture] - University of Washington Digital Collection\n{{Pike Place Market}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Steinbrueck, Victor}}\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:1985 deaths]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Institute of Architects]]\n[[Category:Modernist architects from the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Mandan, North Dakota]]\n[[Category:University of Washington College of Built Environments alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Washington faculty]]\n[[Category:Writers from Seattle]]\n[[Category:Pike Place Market]]\n[[Category:Architects from Seattle]]\n[[Category:Preservationist architects]]\n[[Category:20th-century American architects]]\n[[Category:20th-century historians]]\n", "name_user": "Hatchens", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Victor_Steinbrueck"}
{"title_page": "Otto Mellies", "text_new": "{{short description|German actress}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Otto Mellies\n| image       = \n| caption     =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1931|1|19|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[S\u0142awno|Schlawe]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|2020|4|26|1931|1|19|df=yes}}\n| death_place = \n| othername   =\n| occupation  = Actor\n| years active = \n}}\n'''Otto Mellies''' (19 January 1931 - 26 April 2020) was a German actor on stage, in film and television, and a voice actor. He was  known for his performance of the title role of Lessing's ''[[Nathan the Wise]]'' on stage 325 times.\n\n== Life and career ==\nMellies was born in [[S\u0142awno|Schlawe]], now S\u0142awno in Poland. At age 16, he applied successfully for acting education at the [[Staatstheater Schwerin]], learning with [[Lucie H\u00f6flich]], the director of drama. He worked at various theatres, such as in Neustrelitz, Stralsund, Rostock and Erfurt, learning a broad repertoire. He played the Tempelherr in Lessing's ''[[Nathan der Weise]]'' in Stralsulnd at age 20.<ref name=\"DEFA\" />\n\nFrom 1956, he was a member of the [[Deutsches Theater Berlin]], engaged by [[Wolfgang Langhoff]]. He turned to character roles such as Pylades in the 1976 production of Goethe's ''Iphigenie'' by Thomas Langhoff, with [[Inge Keller]] in the title role. <!--Friedo Solter,  Alexander Lang, Joachim Gosch--> During his 55 years on stage, he excelled as Lessing's Nathan, staged by Friedo Solter in 1987,<ref name=\"DEFA\" /> which he played 325 times.<ref name=\"Spiegel\" />\n\nMellies died on 26 April 2020.<ref name=\"Spiegel\" /><ref name=\"DEFA\" />\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Film\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n<!--! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes-->\n|-\n| 1957\n| ''[[Hellas ohne G\u00f6tter]]''\n| speaker<ref>[https://www.filmportal.de/film/hellas-ohne-goetter_a82dde40d98a40539e85b89a5ef6fd68 Hellas ohne G\u00f6tter] filmportal.de</ref>\n|-\n| 1959\n| ''[[Intrigue and Love (film)|Intrigue and Love]]''\n| Ferdinand\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[According to the Plan]]''\n| Wolf\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Stopped on Track]]''\n| Frank's father Ernst\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Back on Track (film)|Back on Track]]''\n| Rudolf\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+TV\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n<!--! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes-->\n|-\n| 1973\n| ''[[Seventeen Moments of Spring]]''\n| Helmut Kolder\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist\n| refs =\n\n<ref name=\"DEFA\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.defa-stiftung.de/defa/kuenstlerin/otto-mellies/\n| title = Otto Mellies\n| language = de\n| website = [[DEFA]]\n| accessdate = 27 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Spiegel\">{{cite news\n| url = https://www.spiegel.de/kultur/tv/otto-mellies-ist-tot-schauspieler-am-deutschen-theater-berlin-a-e8a8c258-50b8-41e7-8aeb-9ae0c3a6cd5c\n| title = Otto Mellies ist tot\n| language = de\n| work = [[Der Spiegel]]\n| date = 27 April 2020\n| accessdate = 27 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{DNB portal|120963094}}\n* {{IMDb name|577958}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mellies, Otto}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:German male film actors]]\n[[Category:German male stage actors]]\n[[Category:People from S\u0142awno]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Pomerania]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|German actress}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Otto Mellies\n| image       = \n| caption     =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1931|1|19|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[S\u0142awno|Schlawe]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|2020|4|26|1931|1|19|df=yes}}\n| death_place = \n| othername   =\n| occupation  = Actor\n| years active = \n}}\n'''Otto Mellies''' (19 January 1931 - 26 April 2020) was a German actor on stage, in film and television, and a voice actor. He was  known for his performance of the title role of Lessing's ''[[Nathan the Wise]]'' on stage 325 times.\n\n== Life and career ==\nMellies was born in [[S\u0142awno|Schlawe]], now S\u0142awno in Poland. At age 16, he applied successfully for acting education at the [[Staatstheater Schwerin]], learning with [[Lucie H\u00f6flich]], the director of drama. He worked at various theatres, such as in Neustrelitz, Stralsund, Rostock and Erfurt, learning a broad repertoire. He played the Tempelherr in Lessing's ''[[Nathan der Weise]]'' in Stralsulnd at age 20.<ref name=\"DEFA\" />\n\nFrom 1956, he was a member of the [[Deutsches Theater Berlin]], engaged by [[Wolfgang Langhoff]]. He turned to character roles such as Pylades in the 1976 production of Goethe's ''Iphigenie'' by Thomas Langhoff, with [[Inge Keller]] in the title role. <!--Friedo Solter,  Alexander Lang, Joachim Gosch-->. During his 55 years on stage, he excelled as Lessing's Nathan, staged by Friedo Solter in 1987,<ref name=\"DEFA\" /> which he played 325 times.<ref name=\"Spiegel\" />\n\nMellies died on 26 April 2020.<ref name=\"Spiegel\" /><ref name=\"DEFA\" />\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Film\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n<!--! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes-->\n|-\n| 1957\n| ''[[Hellas ohne G\u00f6tter]]''\n| speaker<ref>[https://www.filmportal.de/film/hellas-ohne-goetter_a82dde40d98a40539e85b89a5ef6fd68 Hellas ohne G\u00f6tter] filmportal.de</ref>\n|-\n| 1959\n| ''[[Intrigue and Love (film)|Intrigue and Love]]''\n| Ferdinand\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[According to the Plan]]''\n| Wolf\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Stopped on Track]]''\n| Frank's father Ernst\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Back on Track (film)|Back on Track]]''\n| Rudolf\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+TV\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n<!--! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes-->\n|-\n| 1973\n| ''[[Seventeen Moments of Spring]]''\n| Helmut Kolder\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist\n| refs =\n\n<ref name=\"DEFA\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.defa-stiftung.de/defa/kuenstlerin/otto-mellies/\n| title = Otto Mellies\n| language = de\n| website = [[DEFA]]\n| accessdate = 27 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Spiegel\">{{cite news\n| url = https://www.spiegel.de/kultur/tv/otto-mellies-ist-tot-schauspieler-am-deutschen-theater-berlin-a-e8a8c258-50b8-41e7-8aeb-9ae0c3a6cd5c\n| title = Otto Mellies ist tot\n| language = de\n| work = [[Der Spiegel]]\n| date = 27 April 2020\n| accessdate = 27 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{DNB portal|120963094}}\n* {{IMDb name|577958}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mellies, Otto}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:German male film actors]]\n[[Category:German male stage actors]]\n[[Category:People from S\u0142awno]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Pomerania]]\n", "name_user": "Gerda Arendt", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife and career", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Otto_Mellies"}
{"title_page": "Harvard\u2013Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics", "text_new": "{{Correct title|Center for Astrophysics {{!}} Harvard & Smithsonian}}\n\n{{refimprove|date=October 2019}}\n{{short description|Astronomical observatory in Massachusetts, US}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name                = Center for Astrophysics {{!}} Harvard & Smithsonian\n| full_name           = \n| image               = Center for Astrophysics at Harvard.jpg\n| image_size          = 420px\n| caption             = The Center for Astrophysics {{!}} Harvard & Smithsonian (CfA) Headquarters in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]]. Known as the \"Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics\" since its founding in 1973, the CfA rebranded to its current name in 2018.\n| logo                = CfA_Horizontal_RGB.png\n| logo_size           = 420px\n| logo_alt            = \n| abbreviation        = CfA\n| established         = 1973\n| leader_title        = Director\n| leader_name         = [[Charles R. Alcock]]\n| purpose             = Research in [[astronomy]], [[astrophysics]], Earth, and [[space sciences]]\n| headquarters        = 60 Garden Street, [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], [[United States]]\n| staff               = 850+\n| website             = {{url|http://www.cfa.harvard.edu/}}\n| formerly            = Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics\n}}\nThe '''Center for Astrophysics | Harvard & Smithsonian (CfA)''' is an [[astrophysics]] [[research institute]] jointly operated by the [[Harvard College Observatory]] and [[Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory]]. Founded in 1973 and headquartered in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], the CfA leads a broad program of research in [[astronomy]], [[astrophysics]], [[earth science|Earth]] and [[space science]]s, as well as [[science education]]. The CfA either leads or participates in the development and operations of more than fifteen [[Ground-based telescope|ground-]] and [[Space telescope|space-based]] astronomical research [[Observatory|observatories]] across the [[electromagnetic spectrum]], including the forthcoming [[Giant Magellan Telescope]] (GMT) and the ''[[Chandra X-ray Observatory]],'' one of [[NASA]]'s [[Great Observatories program|Great Observatories]]. \n\nHosting more than 850 scientists, engineers, and support staff, the CfA is among the largest astronomical research institutes in the world<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.natureindex.com/institution-outputs/united-states-of-america-usa/harvard-smithsonian-center-for-astrophysics-cfa/513906bf34d6b65e6a000650/Physical%20Sciences|title=Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics (CfA)|website=www.natureindex.com|access-date=2020-04-26}}</ref>. Its projects have included [[Nobel Prize]]-winning advances in [[cosmology]] and [[High-energy astronomy|high energy astrophysics]], the discovery of many [[Exoplanet|exoplanets]], and the [[Event Horizon Telescope|first image of a black hole]]. Known for most of its history as the \"Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics\", the CfA [[Rebranding|rebranded]] in 2018 to its current name in an effort to reflect its unique status as a joint collaboration between [[Harvard University]] and the [[Smithsonian Institution]]. The CfA's current Director (since 2004) is [[Charles R. Alcock]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.harvard.edu/gazette/2004/05.20/01-alcock.html|title=Alcock to lead the CfA: Astrophysicist noted for 'dark matter' studies to take helm at observatories|date=2004-05-20|accessdate=2007-12-25|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060903100001/http://www.news.harvard.edu/gazette/2004/05.20/01-alcock.html|archive-date=2006-09-03|publisher=Harvard Gazette}}</ref>, who succeeds [[Irwin I. Shapiro]] (Director from 1982 to 2004) and [[George B. Field]] (Director from 1973 to 1982). \n\n== History of the CfA ==\nThe Center for Astrophysics | Harvard & Smithsonian is not formally an independent legal organization, but rather an [https://www.lawinsider.com/dictionary/5-institutional-entitythe-term institutional entity] operated under a [[Memorandum of understanding|Memorandum of Understanding]] between [[Harvard University]] and the [[Smithsonian Institution]]. This collaboration was formalized on [[July 1973|July 1, 1973]], with the goal of coordinating the related research activities of the [[Harvard College Observatory]] (HCO) and the [[Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory]] (SAO) under the leadership of a single [https://www.cfa.harvard.edu/do/ Director], and housed within the same [https://goo.gl/maps/GdnGb2H9sJCeF6WK9 complex of buildings] on the [[Harvard University|Harvard campus]] in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]]. The CfA's own history is therefore much shorter than the two fully independent organizations that comprise it. HCO and SAO share a combined history of more than 300 years, including major milestones in [[History of astronomy|astronomical history]]. \n\n=== History of the Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory (SAO) ===\n{{Main|Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory}}\n\n[[File:The_Smithsonian_Astrophysical_Observatory_on_the_National_Mall,_1909.png|thumb|420px|The [[Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory]] (SAO) on the South Yard of the [[Smithsonian Castle]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], in 1909. In 1973, SAO moved to [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] and unified with the [[Harvard College Observatory]] to form the Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics.  ]]\n\n[[Samuel Pierpont Langley]], the third [[Secretary of the Smithsonian Institution|Secretary of the Smithsonian]], founded what was to become the Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory on the south yard of the [[Smithsonian Institution Building|Smithsonian Castle]] (on the U.S. [[National Mall]]) on March 1,[[1890s|1890]]. The Astrophysical Observatory's initial, primary purpose was to \"''record the amount and character of the Sun's heat''<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=DeVorkin|first=David H.|title=\"Fred Whipple's Empire: The Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory, 1955-1973\"|publisher=Smithsonian Institution Scholarly Press|year=2018|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\". [[Charles Greeley Abbot]] was named SAO's first director, and the observatory operated [[Solar telescope|solar telescopes]] to take daily measurements of the [[Sun]]'s intensity in different regions of the [[Electromagnetic spectrum|optical electromagnetic spectrum]]. In doing so, the observatory enabled Abbot to make critical refinements to the [[Solar constant]], as well as to serendipitously discover [[Solar cycle|Solar variability]].    \n\nIn 1955, the scientific headquarters of SAO moved from [[Washington, D.C.]] to [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] to affiliate with the [[Harvard College Observatory]] (HCO)<ref name=\":0\" />. [[Fred Lawrence Whipple]], then the chairman of the Harvard Astronomy Department, was named the new director of SAO. The strong collaborative relationship and unified Directorship across SAO and HCO therefore predates the creation of the CfA by 17 years. SAO's move to Harvard's campus also resulted in a rapid expansion of its research program. Following the launch of ''[[Sputnik 1|Sputnik]]'' (the world's first human-made satellite) in 1957, SAO accepted a national challenge<ref>{{Citation|last=Spiller|first=James|title=Rising to the Sputnik Challenge|date=2015|url=https://doi.org/10.1057/9781137507877_2|work=Frontiers for the American Century: Outer Space, Antarctica, and Cold War Nationalism|pages=21\u201364|editor-last=Spiller|editor-first=James|series=Palgrave Studies in the History of Science and Technology|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan US|language=en|doi=10.1057/9781137507877_2|isbn=978-1-137-50787-7|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> to create a worldwide satellite-tracking network, collaborating with the [[United States Air Force]] on [[Project Space Track (1957-1961)|Project Space Track]].    \n\nWith the creation of [[NASA]] the following year and throughout the [[Space Race|space race]], SAO led major efforts in the development of [[Space telescope|orbiting observatories]] and large [[Ground-based telescope|ground-based telescopes]], laboratory and [[theoretical astrophysics]], as well as the [[Computer|application of computers]] to astrophysical problems.   \n\n=== History of Harvard College Observatory (HCO) ===\n{{Main|Harvard College Observatory}}\n\n[[File:Harvard-Observatory-1899.jpg|thumb|420px|The [[Harvard College Observatory]], circa 1899. [[Harvard Square]] and the City of [[Boston]] are in the distant background. Most of the telescope domes in the foreground are no longer standing, but the largest dome in the top right of the photo, housing the 1847 \"Great Refractor\", still remains. The Great Refractor was the largest telescope in the United States until 1867. It was the first telescope to take a photographic image of the [[Moon]].]]\n\nIn [[1839]], the [[Harvard Corporation]] voted to appoint [[William Cranch Bond]], a prominent [[Boston]] clockmaker, as \"Astronomical Observer to the University\" (at no salary). This marked the founding of the Harvard College Observatory. HCO's first telescope, the 15-inch Great Refractor, was installed in 1847. That telescope was the largest in the United States from installation until 1867.\n\nBetween 1847 and 1852 Bond and pioneer photographer [[John Adams Whipple]] used the Great Refractor telescope to produce images of the moon that are remarkable in their clarity of detail and aesthetic power. This was the largest telescope in North America at that time, and their images of the moon took the prize for technical excellence in photography at the 1851 [[The Great Exhibition|Great Exhibition]] at [[The Crystal Palace]] in [[London]]. On the night of July 16\u201317, 1850, Whipple and Bond made the first [[daguerreotype]] of a star ([[Vega]]).\n\nHarvard College Observatory is historically important to astronomy, as many women including [[Annie Jump Cannon]], [[Henrietta Swan Leavitt]], [[Cecilia Payne-Gaposchkin]], and [[Williamina Fleming]] performed pivotal [[stellar classification]] research. Cannon and Leavitt were hired initially as \"[[Harvard Computers|computers]]\" to perform calculations and examine stellar photographs, but later made insightful connections in their research.\n\n=== Joint history as the Center for Astrophysics (CfA) ===\n\n\n[[File:Black hole - Messier 87 crop max res.jpg|thumb|420px|The first image of the [[photon ring]] of a [[black hole]] ([[M87*]]), captured by the [[Event Horizon Telescope]]. The CfA plays a central role in the project<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cfa.harvard.edu/news/2019-12|title=CfA Plays Central Role In Capturing Landmark Black Hole Image|date=2019-04-09|website=www.cfa.harvard.edu/|language=en|access-date=2020-04-27}}</ref>.  ]]\n\n\n\n== Organizational Structure ==\n\n=== Scientific Divisions within the CfA ===\n\n* Atomic and Molecular Physics (AMP)\n* High Energy Astrophysics (HEA)\n* Optical and Infrared Astronomy (OIR)\n* Radio and Geoastronomy (RG)\n* Solar, Stellar, and Planetary Sciences (SSP)\n* Theoretical Astrophysics (TA)\n\n=== Scientific Departments at the CfA ===\n\n*[https://astronomy.fas.harvard.edu/ Harvard University Department of Astronomy]\n*[https://www.cfa.harvard.edu/sed/ Science Education Department]\n\n=== Centers hosted at the CfA ===\n\n*[https://cxc.harvard.edu/ ''Chandra'' X-ray Center] (CXC), the science operations center for [[NASA]]'s ''[[Chandra X-ray Observatory]]''\n*[https://itc.cfa.harvard.edu/ Institute for Theory and Computation] (ITC)\n* Institute for Theoretical Atomic, Molecular, and Optical Physics (ITAMP)\n* Center for Parallel Astrophysical Computing (CPAC)\n*[[Minor Planet Center]] (MPC)\n* Telescope Data Center (TDC)\n* Radio Telescope Data Center (RTDC)\n\n=== Administrative and Technical Groups ===\n\n* Central Engineering\n* Computation Facility\n* Director's Office\n* John G. Wolbach Library\n* Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory Financial Management\n* Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory Human Resources\n* Travel and Special Events\n* Harvard College Observatory Administrative Office\n* Sponsored Programs and Procurement\n\n== Observatories operated with CfA participation ==\n\n\n=== Ground-based observatories ===\n\n* [[Fred Lawrence Whipple Observatory]]\n* [[Magellan telescopes]]\n* [[MMT Observatory]]\n* [[South Pole Telescope]]\n* [[Submillimeter Array]]\n* [[CfA 1.2 m Millimeter-Wave Telescope|1.2-Meter Millimeter-Wave Telescope]]\n* [[VERITAS|Very Energetic Radiation Imaging Telescope Array System (VERITAS)]]\n\n=== Space-based observatories ===\n\n*[[Chandra X-ray Observatory|''Chandra X-ray Observatory'']]\n*[[Hinode (satellite)|''Hinode'']]\n*[[Kepler mission|''Kepler'']]\n*[[Solar Dynamics Observatory|''Solar Dynamics Observatory (SDO)'']]\n*[[SOHO spacecraft|''Solar and Heliospheric Observatory (SOHO)'']]\n*[[Spitzer Space Telescope|''Spitzer Space Telescope'']]\n\n=== Planned future observatories ===\n\n*[[Lynx X-ray Observatory|''Lynx X-ray Observatory'']]\n*[[Giant Magellan Telescope]]\n*[[Murchison Widefield Array]]\n*[[Square Kilometer Array]]\n*[[Pan-STARRS]]\n*[[Large Synoptic Survey Telescope]]\n\n== Directors ==\n*[[George B. Field]]: 1973\u20131982\n*[[Irwin I. Shapiro]]: 1982\u20132004\n*[[Charles R. Alcock]]: 2004\u2013Present\n\n== Funding sources ==\n\nThe Center receives 70% of its funding from [[NASA]], 22% from [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian]] federal funds and 4% from the [[National Science Foundation]]. The remaining 4% comes from contributors including the [[United States Department of Energy]], the [[Annenberg Foundation]], and gifts and endowments.{{fact|date=March 2018}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.cfa.harvard.edu/ CfA Homepage]\n\n{{Harvard}}\n{{Smithsonian Institution}}\n{{Coord|42.38146|-71.12837|type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics}}\n[[Category:Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics| 01]]\n[[Category:Astronomical observatories in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Astronomy institutes and departments]]\n[[Category:Astrophysics institutes]]\n[[Category:Harvard University]]\n[[Category:Smithsonian Institution research programs]]\n[[Category:Research institutes in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Research institutes established in 1973]]\n[[Category:1973 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Harvard University buildings]]\n", "text_old": "{{Correct title|Center for Astrophysics {{!}} Harvard & Smithsonian}}\n\n{{refimprove|date=October 2019}}\n{{short description|Astronomical observatory in Massachusetts, US}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name                = Center for Astrophysics {{!}} Harvard & Smithsonian\n| full_name           = \n| image               = Center for Astrophysics at Harvard.jpg\n| image_size          = 420px\n| caption             = The Center for Astrophysics {{!}} Harvard & Smithsonian (CfA) Headquarters in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]]. Known as the \"Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics\" since its founding in 1973, the CfA rebranded to its current name in 2018.\n| logo                = CfA_Horizontal_RGB.png\n| logo_size           = 420px\n| logo_alt            = \n| abbreviation        = CfA\n| established         = 1973\n| leader_title        = Director\n| leader_name         = [[Charles R. Alcock]]\n| purpose             = Research in [[astronomy]], [[astrophysics]], Earth, and [[space sciences]]\n| headquarters        = 60 Garden Street, [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], [[United States]]\n| staff               = 850+\n| website             = {{url|http://www.cfa.harvard.edu/}}\n| formerly            = Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics\n}}\nThe '''Center for Astrophysics | Harvard & Smithsonian (CfA)''' is an [[astrophysics]] [[research institute]] jointly operated by the [[Harvard College Observatory]] and [[Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory]]. Founded in 1973 and headquartered in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], the CfA leads a broad program of research in [[astronomy]], [[astrophysics]], [[earth science|Earth]] and [[space science]]s, as well as [[science education]]. The CfA either leads or participates in the development and operations of more than fifteen [[Ground-based telescope|ground-]] and [[Space telescope|space-based]] astronomical research [[Observatory|observatories]] across the [[electromagnetic spectrum]], including the forthcoming [[Giant Magellan Telescope]] (GMT) and the ''[[Chandra X-ray Observatory]],'' one of [[NASA]]'s [[Great Observatories program|Great Observatories]]. \n\nHosting more than 850 scientists, engineers, and support staff, the CfA is among the largest astronomical research institutes in the world<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.natureindex.com/institution-outputs/united-states-of-america-usa/harvard-smithsonian-center-for-astrophysics-cfa/513906bf34d6b65e6a000650/Physical%20Sciences|title=Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics (CfA)|website=www.natureindex.com|access-date=2020-04-26}}</ref>. Its projects have included [[Nobel Prize]]-winning advances in [[cosmology]] and [[High-energy astronomy|high energy astrophysics]], the discovery of many [[Exoplanet|exoplanets]], and the [[Event Horizon Telescope|first image of a black hole]]. Known for most of its history as the \"Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics\", the CfA [[Rebranding|rebranded]] in 2018 to its current name in an effort to reflect its unique status as a joint collaboration between [[Harvard University]] and the [[Smithsonian Institution]]. The CfA's current Director (since 2004) is [[Charles R. Alcock]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.harvard.edu/gazette/2004/05.20/01-alcock.html|title=Alcock to lead the CfA: Astrophysicist noted for 'dark matter' studies to take helm at observatories|date=2004-05-20|accessdate=2007-12-25|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060903100001/http://www.news.harvard.edu/gazette/2004/05.20/01-alcock.html|archive-date=2006-09-03|publisher=Harvard Gazette}}</ref>, who succeeds [[Irwin I. Shapiro]] (Director from 1982 to 2004) and [[George B. Field]] (Director from 1973 to 1982). \n\n== History of the CfA ==\nThe Center for Astrophysics | Harvard & Smithsonian is not formally an independent legal organization, but rather an [https://www.lawinsider.com/dictionary/5-institutional-entitythe-term institutional entity] operated under a [[Memorandum of understanding|Memorandum of Understanding]] between [[Harvard University]] and the [[Smithsonian Institution]]. This collaboration was formalized on [[July 1973|July 1, 1973]], with the goal of coordinating the related research activities of the [[Harvard College Observatory]] (HCO) and the [[Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory]] (SAO) under the leadership of a single [https://www.cfa.harvard.edu/do/ Director], and housed within the same [https://goo.gl/maps/GdnGb2H9sJCeF6WK9 complex of buildings] on the [[Harvard University|Harvard campus]] in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]]. The CfA's own history is therefore much shorter than the two fully independent organizations that comprise it. HCO and SAO share a combined history of more than 300 years, including major milestones in [[History of astronomy|astronomical history]]. \n\n=== History of the Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory (SAO) ===\n{{Main|Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory}}\n\n[[File:The_Smithsonian_Astrophysical_Observatory_on_the_National_Mall,_1909.png|thumb|420px|The [[Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory]] (SAO) on the South Yard of the [[Smithsonian Castle]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], in 1909. In 1973, SAO moved to [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] and unified with the [[Harvard College Observatory]] to form the Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics.  ]]\n\n[[Samuel Pierpont Langley]], the third [[Secretary of the Smithsonian Institution|Secretary of the Smithsonian]], founded what was to become the Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory on the south yard of the [[Smithsonian Institution Building|Smithsonian Castle]] (on the U.S. [[National Mall]]) on March 1,[[1890s|1890]]. The Astrophysical Observatory's initial, primary purpose was to \"''record the amount and character of the Sun's heat''<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=DeVorkin|first=David H.|title=\"Fred Whipple's Empire: The Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory, 1955-1973\"|publisher=Smithsonian Institution Scholarly Press|year=2018|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\". [[Charles Greeley Abbot]] was named SAO's first director, and the observatory operated [[Solar telescope|solar telescopes]] to take daily measurements of the [[Sun]]'s intensity in different regions of the [[Electromagnetic spectrum|optical electromagnetic spectrum]]. In doing so, the observatory enabled Abbot to make critical refinements to the [[Solar constant]], as well as to serendipitously discover [[Solar cycle|Solar variability]].    \n\nIn 1955, the scientific headquarters of SAO moved from [[Washington, D.C.]] to [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] to affiliate with the [[Harvard College Observatory]] (HCO)<ref name=\":0\" />. [[Fred Lawrence Whipple]], then the chairman of the Harvard Astronomy Department, was named the new director of SAO. The strong collaborative relationship and unified Directorship across SAO and HCO therefore predates the creation of the CfA by 17 years. SAO's move to Harvard's campus also resulted in a rapid expansion of its research program. Following the launch of ''[[Sputnik 1|Sputnik]]'' (the world's first human-made satellite) in 1957, SAO accepted a national challenge<ref>{{Citation|last=Spiller|first=James|title=Rising to the Sputnik Challenge|date=2015|url=https://doi.org/10.1057/9781137507877_2|work=Frontiers for the American Century: Outer Space, Antarctica, and Cold War Nationalism|pages=21\u201364|editor-last=Spiller|editor-first=James|series=Palgrave Studies in the History of Science and Technology|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan US|language=en|doi=10.1057/9781137507877_2|isbn=978-1-137-50787-7|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> to create a worldwide satellite-tracking network, collaborating with the [[United States Air Force]] on [[Project Space Track (1957-1961)|Project Space Track]].    \n\nWith the the creation of [[NASA]] the following year and throughout the [[Space Race|space race]], SAO led major efforts in the development of [[Space telescope|orbiting observatories]] and large [[Ground-based telescope|ground-based telescopes]], laboratory and [[theoretical astrophysics]], as well as the [[Computer|application of computers]] to astrophysical problems.   \n\n=== History of Harvard College Observatory (HCO) ===\n{{Main|Harvard College Observatory}}\n\n[[File:Harvard-Observatory-1899.jpg|thumb|420px|The [[Harvard College Observatory]], circa 1899. [[Harvard Square]] and the City of [[Boston]] are in the distant background. Most of the telescope domes in the foreground are no longer standing, but the largest dome in the top right of the photo, housing the 1847 \"Great Refractor\", still remains. The Great Refractor was the largest telescope in the United States until 1867. It was the first telescope to take a photographic image of the [[Moon]].]]\n\nIn [[1839]], the [[Harvard Corporation]] voted to appoint [[William Cranch Bond]], a prominent [[Boston]] clockmaker, as \"Astronomical Observer to the University\" (at no salary). This marked the founding of the Harvard College Observatory. HCO's first telescope, the 15-inch Great Refractor, was installed in 1847. That telescope was the largest in the United States from installation until 1867.\n\nBetween 1847 and 1852 Bond and pioneer photographer [[John Adams Whipple]] used the Great Refractor telescope to produce images of the moon that are remarkable in their clarity of detail and aesthetic power. This was the largest telescope in North America at that time, and their images of the moon took the prize for technical excellence in photography at the 1851 [[The Great Exhibition|Great Exhibition]] at [[The Crystal Palace]] in [[London]]. On the night of July 16\u201317, 1850, Whipple and Bond made the first [[daguerreotype]] of a star ([[Vega]]).\n\nHarvard College Observatory is historically important to astronomy, as many women including [[Annie Jump Cannon]], [[Henrietta Swan Leavitt]], [[Cecilia Payne-Gaposchkin]], and [[Williamina Fleming]] performed pivotal [[stellar classification]] research. Cannon and Leavitt were hired initially as \"[[Harvard Computers|computers]]\" to perform calculations and examine stellar photographs, but later made insightful connections in their research.\n\n=== Joint history as the Center for Astrophysics (CfA) ===\n\n\n[[File:Black hole - Messier 87 crop max res.jpg|thumb|420px|The first image of the [[photon ring]] of a [[black hole]] ([[M87*]]), captured by the [[Event Horizon Telescope]]. The CfA plays a central role in the project<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cfa.harvard.edu/news/2019-12|title=CfA Plays Central Role In Capturing Landmark Black Hole Image|date=2019-04-09|website=www.cfa.harvard.edu/|language=en|access-date=2020-04-27}}</ref>.  ]]\n\n\n\n== Organizational Structure ==\n\n=== Scientific Divisions within the CfA ===\n\n* Atomic and Molecular Physics (AMP)\n* High Energy Astrophysics (HEA)\n* Optical and Infrared Astronomy (OIR)\n* Radio and Geoastronomy (RG)\n* Solar, Stellar, and Planetary Sciences (SSP)\n* Theoretical Astrophysics (TA)\n\n=== Scientific Departments at the CfA ===\n\n*[https://astronomy.fas.harvard.edu/ Harvard University Department of Astronomy]\n*[https://www.cfa.harvard.edu/sed/ Science Education Department]\n\n=== Centers hosted at the CfA ===\n\n*[https://cxc.harvard.edu/ ''Chandra'' X-ray Center] (CXC), the science operations center for [[NASA]]'s ''[[Chandra X-ray Observatory]]''\n*[https://itc.cfa.harvard.edu/ Institute for Theory and Computation] (ITC)\n* Institute for Theoretical Atomic, Molecular, and Optical Physics (ITAMP)\n* Center for Parallel Astrophysical Computing (CPAC)\n*[[Minor Planet Center]] (MPC)\n* Telescope Data Center (TDC)\n* Radio Telescope Data Center (RTDC)\n\n=== Administrative and Technical Groups ===\n\n* Central Engineering\n* Computation Facility\n* Director's Office\n* John G. Wolbach Library\n* Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory Financial Management\n* Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory Human Resources\n* Travel and Special Events\n* Harvard College Observatory Administrative Office\n* Sponsored Programs and Procurement\n\n== Observatories operated with CfA participation ==\n\n\n=== Ground-based observatories ===\n\n* [[Fred Lawrence Whipple Observatory]]\n* [[Magellan telescopes]]\n* [[MMT Observatory]]\n* [[South Pole Telescope]]\n* [[Submillimeter Array]]\n* [[CfA 1.2 m Millimeter-Wave Telescope|1.2-Meter Millimeter-Wave Telescope]]\n* [[VERITAS|Very Energetic Radiation Imaging Telescope Array System (VERITAS)]]\n\n=== Space-based observatories ===\n\n*[[Chandra X-ray Observatory|''Chandra X-ray Observatory'']]\n*[[Hinode (satellite)|''Hinode'']]\n*[[Kepler mission|''Kepler'']]\n*[[Solar Dynamics Observatory|''Solar Dynamics Observatory (SDO)'']]\n*[[SOHO spacecraft|''Solar and Heliospheric Observatory (SOHO)'']]\n*[[Spitzer Space Telescope|''Spitzer Space Telescope'']]\n\n=== Planned future observatories ===\n\n*[[Lynx X-ray Observatory|''Lynx X-ray Observatory'']]\n*[[Giant Magellan Telescope]]\n*[[Murchison Widefield Array]]\n*[[Square Kilometer Array]]\n*[[Pan-STARRS]]\n*[[Large Synoptic Survey Telescope]]\n\n== Directors ==\n*[[George B. Field]]: 1973\u20131982\n*[[Irwin I. Shapiro]]: 1982\u20132004\n*[[Charles R. Alcock]]: 2004\u2013Present\n\n== Funding sources ==\n\nThe Center receives 70% of its funding from [[NASA]], 22% from [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian]] federal funds and 4% from the [[National Science Foundation]]. The remaining 4% comes from contributors including the [[United States Department of Energy]], the [[Annenberg Foundation]], and gifts and endowments.{{fact|date=March 2018}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.cfa.harvard.edu/ CfA Homepage]\n\n{{Harvard}}\n{{Smithsonian Institution}}\n{{Coord|42.38146|-71.12837|type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics}}\n[[Category:Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics| 01]]\n[[Category:Astronomical observatories in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Astronomy institutes and departments]]\n[[Category:Astrophysics institutes]]\n[[Category:Harvard University]]\n[[Category:Smithsonian Institution research programs]]\n[[Category:Research institutes in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Research institutes established in 1973]]\n[[Category:1973 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Harvard University buildings]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harvard%E2%80%93Smithsonian_Center_for_Astrophysics"}
{"title_page": "Digi Communications", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Digi Telecommunications}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name        = Digi Communications NV\n| logo        = Digi Logo.png\n| type        = [[Public limited company]]\n| traded_as   = {{BVB|DIGI}}\n| area_served = [[Romania]]<br>[[Hungary]]<br>[[Spain]]<br>[[Italy]]\n| key_people  = [[Zolt\u00e1n Tesz\u00e1ri]] (President)<br>Serghei Bulgac (CEO)\n| industry    = [[Telecommunications]]\n| predecessor = TVS Holding Brasov (1992)<br> Kappa (1993)\n| products    = [[Cable television]]<br> [[Satellite television]]<br> [[Broadband internet]]<br> [[landline|Fixed-line telephony]]<br> [[Mobile telephony]]<br> [[Television production]]<br> [[Pay television]]\n| revenue     = {{Increase}} [[Euro|\u20ac]]1,186 billion <small>(2019)<ref name=\"report\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.digi-communications.ro/en/see-file/Annual-report-2019.pdf |title=Annual Report |publisher=Digi Communications}}</ref>\n| net_income  = {{Increase}} \u20ac40,584 million <small>(2019)<ref name=\"report\"/>\n| num_employees = 16,912 <small>(2019)<ref name=\"report\"/> \n| homepage    = {{URL|http://digi-communications.ro/}}\n| foundation  = 1994 <br> 2000 (Cable Communications NV holding company)\n| location    = [[Bucharest]], Romania\n}}\n\n'''Digi Communications''', also known as '''RCS & RDS''', is a [[Romanian]] [[telecommunication]] [[holding company]] operating in Romania, [[Hungary]], [[Spain]] and [[Italy]].<ref name=\"tmcnet\">{{cite web|url=https://www.digi-communications.ro/ro/despre-noi|title=Despre noi|date=|publisher=Digi Communications|language=romanian}}</ref> Digi was founded by [[Zolt\u00e1n Tesz\u00e1ri]], who is the majority owner, and it is listed on the [[Bucharest Stock Exchange]] since 16 May 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.capital.ro/exclusiv-cine-se-afla-cu-adevarat-in-spatele.html |title=EXCLUSIV! Cine se afl\u0103 cu adev\u0103rat \u00een spatele imperiului DIGI \u2013 RCS & RDS! Povestea secret\u0103 a miliardarului f\u0103r\u0103 chip. Detalii pe care nimeni nu le-a \u0219tiut p\u00e2n\u0103 acum. Dezv\u0103luiri \u00een premier\u0103 din partea unor apropia\u021bi |publisher=capital.ro |date=3 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nHaving a market share of 51% on the internet in 2019, connecting almost all subscribers to internet via fiber optics since 2006, contributed to the Romanian's status as a country with one of the highest fixed broadband internet speeds in the world.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.akamai.com/us/en/multimedia/documents/content/akamai-state-of-the-internet-report-q3-2014.pdf |title=Akamai's state of the internet report Q3 2014 |publisher=akamai.com |date=2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.speedtest.net/global-index |title=Global Speeds March 2020 |publisher=speedtest.net |date=March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.statista.com/chart/7246/the-countries-with-the-fastest-internet/ |title=The Countries with the Fastest Internet |publisher=statis.com |date=10 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n=== First cable networks ===\nIn 1992 TVS Holding Brasov was developed by Zolt\u00e1n Tesz\u00e1ri, Ioan Bendei and other buinessmens. The company offered cable television services in [[Brasov]] and [[Timisoara]]. In 1993 Zolt\u00e1n Tesz\u00e1ri co-founded Kappa cable company in Bucharest. In 1996, the shareholders decided to divide the Kappa network into two equal parts. Half owned by Zolta Tzesari merged with Analog CATV SA cable company in Bucharest. The other half was bought in 2000 by [[Astral Telecom]], which in 2005 was merged with [[UPC Romania]] (now [[Vodafone Romania]]). This separation of the company led to the division of the areas in Bucharest between the two companies for 10 years. \n\nA cable network was built in [[Chisinau]], [[Republic of Moldova]] in 1995, which was later sold.\n\n=== Development ===\n\nIn 1997 the company changed its name to '''Romania Cable Systems SA''' ('''RCS'''). Same year it is established '''Romania Data System SA''' ('''RDS''') which offers internet services. Among the investors in the company from the beginning until the listing on the stock exchange were Carpathian Cable Investments S.a.R.L. from 1998 and Celest Limited from 1999. \n\nThe company entered Hungary in November 1998 after buying 15 small and medium cable companies in [[Budapest]] and 3 other cities. Between December 1999 and January 2000, the first cable networks were acquired in [[Slovakia]], where Slovakia Cable Systems (SCS) was 95% owned by RCS.\n\nIn April 2000, the project to build a 4,200 km national [[fiber optic]] network was initiated.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rcs.ro/despre.php |title=Romania Cable Systems |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040608074723/http://www.rcs.ro/despre.php |archivedate=8 June 2004}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, after the liberalization of the market, the [[landline|fixed telephony]] service was launched in Romania. Digi TV [[satellite television]] platform was first launched in Romania in December 2004, followed by launches in Hungary in February 2006, in the [[Czech Republic]] and Slovakia in August 2006 and in [[Croatia]] and [[Serbia]] in December 2006.\n\n=== 2005-2014 ===\n[[Image:RCS & RDS Logo.png|thumb|RCS & RDS logo (2005-2012)|160px]]\nRCS and RDS merged to form RCS & RDS on 26 April 2005. The company focused on rapid development both organically and through acquisitions. The C-Zone network was acquired in 2006, entering certain areas in Bucharest that were not covered due to zone exclusivity. In these areas RCS & RDS kept the brand until 2009.\n\nDigi Slovakia, including the Digi Sport television channels in Slovakia and the Czech Republic, were sold to [[Slovak Telekom]] in 2013.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://technology.informa.com/435165/slovak-telekom-to-buy-digi-slovakia |title=Slovak Telekom to buy Digi Slovakia |publisher=informa.com |date=22 May 2013}}</ref> Also, satellite television subsidiary in the Czech Republic was sold to Lama Energy in march 2015,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.broadbandtvnews.com/2015/03/23/czech-digi-tv-to-be-sold/ |title=Czech Digi TV to be sold |publisher=broadbandtvnews.com |date=23 March 2015}}</ref> which continued to use the Digi brand for other acquired internet and IPTV provider until 1 April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mediaguru.cz/clanky/2020/03/digi-tv-se-od-dubna-meni-na-telly-zavadi-nove-balicky/ |title=Digi TV se od dubna m\u011bn\u00ed na Telly, zav\u00e1d\u00ed nov\u00e9 bal\u00ed\u010dky |publisher=mediaguru.cz |date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\nThe subsidiary in Croatia was sold to [[A1 Telekom Austria]]'s Vipnet (now [[A1 Hrvatska|A1 Croatia]]).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.filmneweurope.com/news/croatia-news/item/105095-rcsrds-sells-digi-tv-croatia-to-vipnet |title=RCS&RDS Sells Digi TV Croatia to Vipnet |publisher=filmneweurope.com |date=13 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Mobile development ===\nIn 2014, the mobile phone service was relaunched, followed by the launch of [[4G]] service in 2015. \n\nSatellite television subsidiary in Serbia was sold to Kopernikus Technology, which in turn was sold to [[Telekom Srbija]] (mts) in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.parabola.cz/clanky/6523/srbska-digi-tv-prodana-spolecnosti-kopernikus-ta-srbskemu-telekomu/ |title=Srbsk\u00e1 Digi TV prod\u00e1na spole\u010dnosti Kopernikus. Ta srbsk\u00e9mu Telekomu\n|publisher=parabola.cz |date=17 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Digi bought the [[Invitel]] cable company in Hungary. After initially receiving approval in May 2018, it was revoked in November 2018, due to finding non-competitive issues in certain areas. These have been resolved and the transaction was completed in March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.media-max.ro/digi-primeste-o-noua-aprobare-privind-tranzactia-invitel/ |title=Digi primeste o noua aprobare privind tranzactia Invitel |publisher=media-max.ro |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Corporate structure ==\n\nRCS & RDS SA it's the Romanian company founded in 1994 by Zolt\u00e1n Tesz\u00e1ri. It's incorporated in the Netherlands since 2000 when Cable Communications NV was establised. It was renamed Digi Communications NV in 2017 when was listed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.capital.ro/digi-vrea-sa-se-listeze-la-bvb-1.html |title=EXCLUSIV: Cable Communications Systems, firma mam\u0103 a RCS&RDS, se transform\u0103 \u00een Digi Communications \u015fi se listeaz\u0103 la BVB |publisher=capital.ro |date=11 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Services ==\n=== Broadband internet ===\n\nDigi implemented [[Fiber to the building|FTTB]] technology on almost the entire network in Romania and Hungary in 2006. Then followed the implementation of GPON in 2008, covering the houses as well. In 2013 started replacing FFTB with [[Fiber to the home|FTTH]]. In 2018 Digi started offering internet services through FTTH in Spain.\n\n=== Mobile telephony ===\n\nThe company launched Digi Mobil in Romania in December 2007 wich offered mobile telephony limited to [[3G]] service only at the time. In 2014, the mobile phone service was relaunched, followed by the launch of [[4G]] service on band 38 in 2015 and on band 1 in 2018.\n\nAfter winning a mobile operator licence in 2014 and numerous delays, the company launched mobile services in Hungary in 2019.\n\nIn Spain, due to the number of Romanians, [[Mobile virtual network operator|MVNO]] mobile telephony services were launched through [[Movistar]] in 2008. Initially, the company attracted Romanians because it offered cheap calls with Romanian networks. Vodafone Spain reacted after 1 year when it started losing customers by offering free calls with Vodafone Romania. This was followed by offers for Latin Americans.\nThen the company started offering internet at a low price, attracting Spanish customers. Digi became the second MVNO operator by number of customers. \n\nFollowing the model in Spain, in 2010 Digi Mobil was launched as MVNO in Italy through [[Telecom Italia|TIM]], but it was not as successful despite the fact that in Italy is a larger number of Romanians. Vodafone Italia began to offer free calls with Vodafone Romania and fixed networks before the launch of Digi Mobil.\n\n=== Cable television ===\n\nThe company offers all channels in one package except premium channels.\n\n=== Television channels ===\n\nIn July 2009, Digi launched the [[Digi Sport]] channels in Romania and Hungary. Then followed the Digi Sport channels in Slovakia and the Czech Republic in August 2010, which have been operated separately since 2013 following the takeover of Digi Slovakia by Slovak Telekom. \n\nIn the summer of 2010, it acquired 50% of Music Channel, which launched Hit Music Channel in January 2012. The company launched a generalist channel in December 2010, but due to the low audience it was closed. The [[premium]] movie channel Digi Film (now Film Now) was launched on 1 February 2011. In 2011 acquired the UTV music TV channel.\n\n[[Digi 24]] TV news channel was launched on 1 March 2012. Following disagreements with [[Discovery Inc.|Discovery]], the company launched 3 thematic channels in October 2012: Digi World, Digi Life and Digi Animal World. On 10 December 2018 was launched Digi 4K.\n\n=== Energy supplier === \n\nIn April 2015, Digi launched the energy supply service. The company had in 2017 the most subscribers on the competitive market from the companies that do not have the distribution infrastructure. In 2019, it increased tariffs by 30% due to a tax added by the government and then by 20%. The company announced that it is gradually giving up the supply service due to the unusual volatility of the electricity price.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://energyreport.ro/index.php/2013-electricitate/2013-stiri-electricitate/2013-energie-electrica/5020-digi-retrage-furnizarea-de-energie-din-grila-de-programe-a-companiei |title=Digi retrage furnizarea de energie din grila de programe a companiei |publisher=energyreport.ro |date=3 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Digi brand ==\n\nRCS & RDS introduced the Digi TV brand for satellite television services in December 2004 in Romania and in 2006 in Hungary, Slovakia, the Czech Republic, Croatia and Serbia. In 2006 the company unified under the Digi brand the cable television, internet and telephony services in Hungary, followed by Slovakia in June 2007. In Romania all the services rebranded Digi in 2009 but it is used together with the old RCS & RDS brand.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.capital.ro/serviciile-rcsrds-unificate-sub-brandul-digi-122482.html |title=Serviciile RCS&RDS, unificate sub brandul Digi |publisher=capital.ro |date=20 July 2009}}</ref>\n\n== Mobile frequencies  ==\nThe following is a list of Digi Mobil mobile frequencies in Romania and Hungary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spectrummonitoring.com/frequencies/index.html |title=List of Mobile Frequencies by Country |publisher=spectrummonitoring.com |date=28 May 2019|accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Romania ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"\n|+Mobile frequencies used by Digi Mobil in Romania\n|-\n! MCC !! MNC !! Frequency !! Band number !! Protocol !! Class !! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 226 || 05 || 900&nbsp;MHz || 8 || GSM || 2G || Voice only GSM network from refarming UMTS 900, used for better indoor coverage. <ref name=\"4G\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.digiromania.ro/anunturi/digi-mobil-introduce-serviciul-de-date-mobile-4g-in-banda-de-frecvente-de-900-mhz-14375 |title=Digi Mobil introduce serviciul de date mobile 4G \u00een band\u0103 de frecvente de 900 Mhz |publisher=digiromania.ro |date=16 October 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 226 || 05 || 900&nbsp;MHz || 8 || UMTS/HSPA/HSPA+ (5Mhz ~21.6 Mbit/s/5.76 Mbit/s) || 3G || RCS&RDS started using this frequency band from 6 April 2014 for better indoor coverage. <ref name=\"4G\"/>\n|-\n| 226 || 05 || 2100&nbsp;MHz || 1 || UMTS/HSPA/HSPA+ (5Mhz ~21.6 Mbit/s/5.76 Mbit/s) || 3G || \n|-\n| 226 || 05 || 2100&nbsp;MHz || 1 || LTE (10Mhz ~75 Mbit/s/37.5 Mbit/s) || 4G || FDD-LTE network launched on 6 October 2016<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.digi24.ro/stiri/sci-tech/lumea-digitala/digi-mobil-anunta-lansarea-serviciul-de-date-4g-si-in-banda-de-frecvente-2100-mhz-582616 |title=Digi Mobil anun\u0163\u0103 lansarea serviciului de date 4G \u0219i \u00een banda de frecven\u021be 2100 Mhz |publisher=digi24.ro |date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 226 || 05 || 900&nbsp;MHz || 8 || LTE (3Mhz ~22.5 Mbit/s/7.5 Mbit/s) || 4G || FDD-LTE network launched in September 2019 from refarming UMTS 900<ref name=\"4G\"/>\n|-\n| 226 || 05 || 2600&nbsp;MHz || 38 || LTE-TDD (20Mhz ~112 Mbit/s) || 4G || TDD-LTE network launched on 1 October 2015\n|-\n| 226 || 05 || 3700&nbsp;MHz || n78 || 5G (50Mhz ~600 Mbit/s) || 5G || TDD 5G network launched on 27 June 2019<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.digiromania.ro/anunturi/digi-mobil-5g-smart-disponibil-de-azi-in-bucuresti-si-in-curand-in-cateva-orase-mari-13049 |title=Digi Mobil 5G Smart disponobil, de zi \u00een Bucure\u0219ti \u0219i \u00een cur\u00e2nd \u00een c\u00e2teva ora\u0219e mari |publisher=digiromania.ro |date=26 June 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== Hungary ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"\n|+Mobile frequencies used on the Digi Mobil in Hungary \n|-\n! MCC !! MNC !! Frequency !! Band number !! Protocol !! Class !! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 216 || 03 || 1800&nbsp;MHz || 3 || GSM || 2G || GSM voice only, no data. Network launched on 28 May 2019 <ref>{{cite web|title=Digi Mobil debuts in Hungary|url=https://www.broadbandtvnews.com/2019/05/28/digi-mobil-debuts-in-hungary/|publisher=broadbandtvnews.com|date=28 May 2019|accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 216 || 03 || 1800&nbsp;MHz || 3 || LTE (22.1/7.5 Mbit/s) || 4G || LTE network launched on 28 May 2019\n|-\n| 216 || 03 || 3500&nbsp;MHz || 42 || 5G (-- Mbit/s) || 5G || TDD network Deployment \n|}\n\n== Shareholding ==\n\nThe majority owner of Digi Communications NV is RCS Management SA, which includes politicians among shareholders. <ref name=\"ghimpele\">[http://www.ghimpele.ro/2013/06/rcs-rds-ioan-bendei-adevarata-fata-a-conducerii-rcs-rds-oameni-de-afaceri-controversati-si-politicieni-pdl/ Adev\u0103rata fa\u0163\u0103 a conducerii RCS-RDS] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609145426/http://www.ghimpele.ro/2013/06/rcs-rds-ioan-bendei-adevarata-fata-a-conducerii-rcs-rds-oameni-de-afaceri-controversati-si-politicieni-pdl/ |date=2013-06-09 }}</ref> In 2016 the shareholders of this company were:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economie.hotnews.ro/stiri-telecom-21405198-rcs-management-firma-controlata-patronul-rcsrds-zoltan-teszari-vrea-rascumpere-10-din-capital-maxim-22-4-milioane-euro-pana-sfarsitul-acestui.htm |title=RCS Management, firma controlata de patronul RCS&RDS, Zoltan Teszari, vrea sa rascumpere 10% din capital cu maxim 22,4 milioane de euro pana la sfarsitul acestui an |publisher=hotnews.ro |date=9 November 2016}}</ref>\n* Zolt\u00e1n Tesz\u00e1ri \u2013 59.23%\n* Cable Communications Systems NV \u2013 2.47%\n* 8 individual associates \u2013 38.30%\n\n== Constroversy == \n\nIn 2012, the operator removed Discovery channels from the grid, motivating that it would have requested too much money for retransmission. During public discussions, Digi offered to redistribute all Discovery channels in a separate package, but Discovery refused.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.economica.net/rcs-rds-a-scos-joi-seara-toate-canalele-discovery-si-de-pe-retelele-sale-de-cablu_39785.html|title=RCS&RDS a scos toate canalele Discovery \u015fi de pe re\u0163elele sale de cablu |publisher=economica.net |date=29 November 2012}}</ref> Only Discovery and TLC returned to the grid in December 2016.\n\nIn 2012, Digi removed the [[Antena 1 (Romania)|Antena TV Group]] channels from the satellite television grid following disagreements. In 2013, the director of Digi, Ioan Bendei was blackmailed to sign the distribution contract by the director of Antena Group, otherwise he will denounce him for corruption of the television rights of the [[Liga I|national football league]].\nThe director of Antena Group was sentenced to prison for blackmail.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ziare.com/sorin-alexandrescu/rcs-rds/directorul-antenelor-a-santajat-rcs-rds-pentru-un-contract-de-7-2-milioane-de-euro-dna-1238473 |title=Directorul Antenelor a santajat RCS-RDS pentru un contract de 7,2 milioane de euro - DNA |publisher=ziare.com |date=31 May 2013}}</ref>\nAfter evidence of corruption made public by a journalist in 2013, the directors of Digi and of the [[Liga Profesionist\u0103 de Fotbal|Professional Football League]] were convicted in January 2019. <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.grupul.ro/category/r/rcs-rds/ |title=Mitic\u0103 Dragomir \u0219i Ioan Bendei condamna\u021bi la 4 ani de \u00eenchisoare cu executare \u00een dosarul RDS |publisher=grupul.ro |date=16 January 2019}}</ref>\nDigi and Antena Group have dropped the litigations in May 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ziare.com/rcs/rds/dupa-ani-de-zile-de-scandaluri-si-procese-rcs-rds-si-antena-group-au-incheiat-un-contract-prin-care-sting-litigiile-1517941 |title=Dupa ani de zile de scandaluri si procese, RCS&RDS si Antena Group au incheiat un contract prin care sting litigiile |publisher=ziare.com |date=18 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn Hungary, Digi was excluded from the auction for 5G licenses in 2019, motivating its decision on assumptions and facts that are supposed to happen. Digi filed an appeal that was not admitted, then sued NMHH, the regulator of the telecommunications market. Meanwhile, the 5G auction has been closed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://economie.hotnews.ro/stiri-telecom-23764805-grupul-digi-cere-anularea-rezultatelor-licitatiei-5g-din-ungaria-alti-trei-operatori-declarati-castigatori-vor-plati-aproximativ-360-milioane-euro-licente.htm |title=Grupul DIGI cere anularea rezultatelor licita\u021biei 5G din Ungaria: Al\u021bi trei operatori, declara\u021bi c\u00e2\u0219tig\u0103tori, vor pl\u0103ti aproximativ 360 de milioane de euro pe licen\u021be |publisher=hotnews.ro |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|digi-communications.ro}}\n* [http://www.digiromania.ro Digi Romania]\n* [http://www.digi.hu Digi Hungary]\n* [http://www.digimobil.es Digi Spain]\n* [http://www.digimobil.it Digi Italy]\n\n{{CATV Europe}}\n{{Romania mobile phone companies}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Bucharest]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies of Romania]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies of Hungary]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies of Spain]]\n[[Category:Internet service providers of Romania]]\n[[Category:Internet service providers of Spain]]\n[[Category:Mobile phone companies of Romania]]\n[[Category:Mobile phone companies of Spain]]\n[[Category:Mobile phone companies of Italy]]\n[[Category:Cable television companies]]\n[[Category:Romanian television networks]]\n[[Category:Romanian brands]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Digi Telecommunications}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name        = Digi Communications NV\n| logo        = Digi Logo.png\n| type        = [[Public limited company]]\n| traded_as   = {{BVB|DIGI}}\n| area_served = [[Romania]]<br>[[Hungary]]<br>[[Spain]]<br>[[Italy]]\n| key_people  = [[Zolt\u00e1n Tesz\u00e1ri]] (President)<br>Serghei Bulgac (CEO)\n| industry    = [[Telecommunications]]\n| predecessor = TVS Holding Brasov (1992)<br> Kappa (1993)\n| products    = [[Cable television]]<br> [[Satellite television]]<br> [[Broadband internet]]<br> [[landline|Fixed-line telephony]]<br> [[Mobile telephony]]<br> [[Television production]]<br> [[Pay television]]\n| revenue     = {{Increase}} [[Euro|\u20ac]]1,186 billion <small>(2019)<ref name=\"report\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.digi-communications.ro/en/see-file/Annual-report-2019.pdf |title=Annual Report |publisher=Digi Communications}}</ref>\n| net_income  = {{Increase}} \u20ac40,584 million <small>(2019)<ref name=\"report\"/>\n| num_employees = 16,912 <small>(2019)<ref name=\"report\"/> \n| homepage    = {{URL|http://digi-communications.ro/}}\n| foundation  = 1994 <br> 2000 (Cable Communications NV holding company)\n| location    = [[Bucharest]], Romania\n}}\n\n'''Digi Communications''', also known as '''RCS & RDS''', is a [[Romanian]] [[telecommunication]] [[holding company]] operating in Romania, [[Hungary]], [[Spain]] and [[Italy]].<ref name=\"tmcnet\">{{cite web|url=https://www.digi-communications.ro/ro/despre-noi|title=Despre noi|date=|publisher=Digi Communications|language=romanian}}</ref> Digi was founded by [[Zolt\u00e1n Tesz\u00e1ri]], who is the the majority owner, and it is listed on the [[Bucharest Stock Exchange]] since 16 May 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.capital.ro/exclusiv-cine-se-afla-cu-adevarat-in-spatele.html |title=EXCLUSIV! Cine se afl\u0103 cu adev\u0103rat \u00een spatele imperiului DIGI \u2013 RCS & RDS! Povestea secret\u0103 a miliardarului f\u0103r\u0103 chip. Detalii pe care nimeni nu le-a \u0219tiut p\u00e2n\u0103 acum. Dezv\u0103luiri \u00een premier\u0103 din partea unor apropia\u021bi |publisher=capital.ro |date=3 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nHaving a market share of 51% on the internet in 2019, connecting almost all subscribers to internet via fiber optics since 2006, contributed to the Romanian's status as a country with one of the highest fixed broadband internet speeds in the world.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.akamai.com/us/en/multimedia/documents/content/akamai-state-of-the-internet-report-q3-2014.pdf |title=Akamai's state of the internet report Q3 2014 |publisher=akamai.com |date=2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.speedtest.net/global-index |title=Global Speeds March 2020 |publisher=speedtest.net |date=March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.statista.com/chart/7246/the-countries-with-the-fastest-internet/ |title=The Countries with the Fastest Internet |publisher=statis.com |date=10 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n=== First cable networks ===\nIn 1992 TVS Holding Brasov was developed by Zolt\u00e1n Tesz\u00e1ri, Ioan Bendei and other buinessmens. The company offered cable television services in [[Brasov]] and [[Timisoara]]. In 1993 Zolt\u00e1n Tesz\u00e1ri co-founded Kappa cable company in Bucharest. In 1996, the shareholders decided to divide the Kappa network into two equal parts. Half owned by Zolta Tzesari merged with Analog CATV SA cable company in Bucharest. The other half was bought in 2000 by [[Astral Telecom]], which in 2005 was merged with [[UPC Romania]] (now [[Vodafone Romania]]). This separation of the company led to the division of the areas in Bucharest between the two companies for 10 years. \n\nA cable network was built in [[Chisinau]], [[Republic of Moldova]] in 1995, which was later sold.\n\n=== Development ===\n\nIn 1997 the company changed its name to '''Romania Cable Systems SA''' ('''RCS'''). Same year it is established '''Romania Data System SA''' ('''RDS''') which offers internet services. Among the investors in the company from the beginning until the listing on the stock exchange were Carpathian Cable Investments S.a.R.L. from 1998 and Celest Limited from 1999. \n\nThe company entered Hungary in November 1998 after buying 15 small and medium cable companies in [[Budapest]] and 3 other cities. Between December 1999 and January 2000, the first cable networks were acquired in [[Slovakia]], where Slovakia Cable Systems (SCS) was 95% owned by RCS.\n\nIn April 2000, the project to build a 4,200 km national [[fiber optic]] network was initiated.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rcs.ro/despre.php |title=Romania Cable Systems |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040608074723/http://www.rcs.ro/despre.php |archivedate=8 June 2004}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, after the liberalization of the market, the [[landline|fixed telephony]] service was launched in Romania. Digi TV [[satellite television]] platform was first launched in Romania in December 2004, followed by launches in Hungary in February 2006, in the [[Czech Republic]] and Slovakia in August 2006 and in [[Croatia]] and [[Serbia]] in December 2006.\n\n=== 2005-2014 ===\n[[Image:RCS & RDS Logo.png|thumb|RCS & RDS logo (2005-2012)|160px]]\nRCS and RDS merged to form RCS & RDS on 26 April 2005. The company focused on rapid development both organically and through acquisitions. The C-Zone network was acquired in 2006, entering certain areas in Bucharest that were not covered due to zone exclusivity. In these areas RCS & RDS kept the brand until 2009.\n\nDigi Slovakia, including the Digi Sport television channels in Slovakia and the Czech Republic, were sold to [[Slovak Telekom]] in 2013.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://technology.informa.com/435165/slovak-telekom-to-buy-digi-slovakia |title=Slovak Telekom to buy Digi Slovakia |publisher=informa.com |date=22 May 2013}}</ref> Also, satellite television subsidiary in the Czech Republic was sold to Lama Energy in march 2015,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.broadbandtvnews.com/2015/03/23/czech-digi-tv-to-be-sold/ |title=Czech Digi TV to be sold |publisher=broadbandtvnews.com |date=23 March 2015}}</ref> which continued to use the Digi brand for other acquired internet and IPTV provider until 1 April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mediaguru.cz/clanky/2020/03/digi-tv-se-od-dubna-meni-na-telly-zavadi-nove-balicky/ |title=Digi TV se od dubna m\u011bn\u00ed na Telly, zav\u00e1d\u00ed nov\u00e9 bal\u00ed\u010dky |publisher=mediaguru.cz |date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\nThe subsidiary in Croatia was sold to [[A1 Telekom Austria]]'s Vipnet (now [[A1 Hrvatska|A1 Croatia]]).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.filmneweurope.com/news/croatia-news/item/105095-rcsrds-sells-digi-tv-croatia-to-vipnet |title=RCS&RDS Sells Digi TV Croatia to Vipnet |publisher=filmneweurope.com |date=13 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Mobile development ===\nIn 2014, the mobile phone service was relaunched, followed by the launch of [[4G]] service in 2015. \n\nSatellite television subsidiary in Serbia was sold to Kopernikus Technology, which in turn was sold to [[Telekom Srbija]] (mts) in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.parabola.cz/clanky/6523/srbska-digi-tv-prodana-spolecnosti-kopernikus-ta-srbskemu-telekomu/ |title=Srbsk\u00e1 Digi TV prod\u00e1na spole\u010dnosti Kopernikus. Ta srbsk\u00e9mu Telekomu\n|publisher=parabola.cz |date=17 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Digi bought the [[Invitel]] cable company in Hungary. After initially receiving approval in May 2018, it was revoked in November 2018, due to finding non-competitive issues in certain areas. These have been resolved and the transaction was completed in March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.media-max.ro/digi-primeste-o-noua-aprobare-privind-tranzactia-invitel/ |title=Digi primeste o noua aprobare privind tranzactia Invitel |publisher=media-max.ro |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Corporate structure ==\n\nRCS & RDS SA it's the Romanian company founded in 1994 by Zolt\u00e1n Tesz\u00e1ri. It's incorporated in the Netherlands since 2000 when Cable Communications NV was establised. It was renamed Digi Communications NV in 2017 when was listed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.capital.ro/digi-vrea-sa-se-listeze-la-bvb-1.html |title=EXCLUSIV: Cable Communications Systems, firma mam\u0103 a RCS&RDS, se transform\u0103 \u00een Digi Communications \u015fi se listeaz\u0103 la BVB |publisher=capital.ro |date=11 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Services ==\n=== Broadband internet ===\n\nDigi implemented [[Fiber to the building|FTTB]] technology on almost the entire network in Romania and Hungary in 2006. Then followed the implementation of GPON in 2008, covering the houses as well. In 2013 started replacing FFTB with [[Fiber to the home|FTTH]]. In 2018 Digi started offering internet services through FTTH in Spain.\n\n=== Mobile telephony ===\n\nThe company launched Digi Mobil in Romania in December 2007 wich offered mobile telephony limited to [[3G]] service only at the time. In 2014, the mobile phone service was relaunched, followed by the launch of [[4G]] service on band 38 in 2015 and on band 1 in 2018.\n\nAfter winning a mobile operator licence in 2014 and numerous delays, the company launched mobile services in Hungary in 2019.\n\nIn Spain, due to the number of Romanians, [[Mobile virtual network operator|MVNO]] mobile telephony services were launched through [[Movistar]] in 2008. Initially, the company attracted Romanians because it offered cheap calls with Romanian networks. Vodafone Spain reacted after 1 year when it started losing customers by offering free calls with Vodafone Romania. This was followed by offers for Latin Americans.\nThen the company started offering internet at a low price, attracting Spanish customers. Digi became the second MVNO operator by number of customers. \n\nFollowing the model in Spain, in 2010 Digi Mobil was launched as MVNO in Italy through [[Telecom Italia|TIM]], but it was not as successful despite the fact that in Italy is a larger number of Romanians. Vodafone Italia began to offer free calls with Vodafone Romania and fixed networks before the launch of Digi Mobil.\n\n=== Cable television ===\n\nThe company offers all channels in one package except premium channels.\n\n=== Television channels ===\n\nIn July 2009, Digi launched the [[Digi Sport]] channels in Romania and Hungary. Then followed the Digi Sport channels in Slovakia and the Czech Republic in August 2010, which have been operated separately since 2013 following the takeover of Digi Slovakia by Slovak Telekom. \n\nIn the summer of 2010, it acquired 50% of Music Channel, which launched Hit Music Channel in January 2012. The company launched a generalist channel in December 2010, but due to the low audience it was closed. The [[premium]] movie channel Digi Film (now Film Now) was launched on 1 February 2011. In 2011 acquired the UTV music TV channel.\n\n[[Digi 24]] TV news channel was launched on 1 March 2012. Following disagreements with [[Discovery Inc.|Discovery]], the company launched 3 thematic channels in October 2012: Digi World, Digi Life and Digi Animal World. On 10 December 2018 was launched Digi 4K.\n\n=== Energy supplier === \n\nIn April 2015, Digi launched the energy supply service. The company had in 2017 the most subscribers on the competitive market from the companies that do not have the distribution infrastructure. In 2019, it increased tariffs by 30% due to a tax added by the government and then by 20%. The company announced that it is gradually giving up the supply service due to the unusual volatility of the electricity price.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://energyreport.ro/index.php/2013-electricitate/2013-stiri-electricitate/2013-energie-electrica/5020-digi-retrage-furnizarea-de-energie-din-grila-de-programe-a-companiei |title=Digi retrage furnizarea de energie din grila de programe a companiei |publisher=energyreport.ro |date=3 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Digi brand ==\n\nRCS & RDS introduced the Digi TV brand for satellite television services in December 2004 in Romania and in 2006 in Hungary, Slovakia, the Czech Republic, Croatia and Serbia. In 2006 the company unified under the Digi brand the cable television, internet and telephony services in Hungary, followed by Slovakia in June 2007. In Romania all the services rebranded Digi in 2009 but it is used together with the old RCS & RDS brand.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.capital.ro/serviciile-rcsrds-unificate-sub-brandul-digi-122482.html |title=Serviciile RCS&RDS, unificate sub brandul Digi |publisher=capital.ro |date=20 July 2009}}</ref>\n\n== Mobile frequencies  ==\nThe following is a list of Digi Mobil mobile frequencies in Romania and Hungary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spectrummonitoring.com/frequencies/index.html |title=List of Mobile Frequencies by Country |publisher=spectrummonitoring.com |date=28 May 2019|accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Romania ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"\n|+Mobile frequencies used by Digi Mobil in Romania\n|-\n! MCC !! MNC !! Frequency !! Band number !! Protocol !! Class !! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 226 || 05 || 900&nbsp;MHz || 8 || GSM || 2G || Voice only GSM network from refarming UMTS 900, used for better indoor coverage. <ref name=\"4G\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.digiromania.ro/anunturi/digi-mobil-introduce-serviciul-de-date-mobile-4g-in-banda-de-frecvente-de-900-mhz-14375 |title=Digi Mobil introduce serviciul de date mobile 4G \u00een band\u0103 de frecvente de 900 Mhz |publisher=digiromania.ro |date=16 October 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 226 || 05 || 900&nbsp;MHz || 8 || UMTS/HSPA/HSPA+ (5Mhz ~21.6 Mbit/s/5.76 Mbit/s) || 3G || RCS&RDS started using this frequency band from 6 April 2014 for better indoor coverage. <ref name=\"4G\"/>\n|-\n| 226 || 05 || 2100&nbsp;MHz || 1 || UMTS/HSPA/HSPA+ (5Mhz ~21.6 Mbit/s/5.76 Mbit/s) || 3G || \n|-\n| 226 || 05 || 2100&nbsp;MHz || 1 || LTE (10Mhz ~75 Mbit/s/37.5 Mbit/s) || 4G || FDD-LTE network launched on 6 October 2016<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.digi24.ro/stiri/sci-tech/lumea-digitala/digi-mobil-anunta-lansarea-serviciul-de-date-4g-si-in-banda-de-frecvente-2100-mhz-582616 |title=Digi Mobil anun\u0163\u0103 lansarea serviciului de date 4G \u0219i \u00een banda de frecven\u021be 2100 Mhz |publisher=digi24.ro |date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 226 || 05 || 900&nbsp;MHz || 8 || LTE (3Mhz ~22.5 Mbit/s/7.5 Mbit/s) || 4G || FDD-LTE network launched in September 2019 from refarming UMTS 900<ref name=\"4G\"/>\n|-\n| 226 || 05 || 2600&nbsp;MHz || 38 || LTE-TDD (20Mhz ~112 Mbit/s) || 4G || TDD-LTE network launched on 1 October 2015\n|-\n| 226 || 05 || 3700&nbsp;MHz || n78 || 5G (50Mhz ~600 Mbit/s) || 5G || TDD 5G network launched on 27 June 2019<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.digiromania.ro/anunturi/digi-mobil-5g-smart-disponibil-de-azi-in-bucuresti-si-in-curand-in-cateva-orase-mari-13049 |title=Digi Mobil 5G Smart disponobil, de zi \u00een Bucure\u0219ti \u0219i \u00een cur\u00e2nd \u00een c\u00e2teva ora\u0219e mari |publisher=digiromania.ro |date=26 June 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== Hungary ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"\n|+Mobile frequencies used on the Digi Mobil in Hungary \n|-\n! MCC !! MNC !! Frequency !! Band number !! Protocol !! Class !! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 216 || 03 || 1800&nbsp;MHz || 3 || GSM || 2G || GSM voice only, no data. Network launched on 28 May 2019 <ref>{{cite web|title=Digi Mobil debuts in Hungary|url=https://www.broadbandtvnews.com/2019/05/28/digi-mobil-debuts-in-hungary/|publisher=broadbandtvnews.com|date=28 May 2019|accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 216 || 03 || 1800&nbsp;MHz || 3 || LTE (22.1/7.5 Mbit/s) || 4G || LTE network launched on 28 May 2019\n|-\n| 216 || 03 || 3500&nbsp;MHz || 42 || 5G (-- Mbit/s) || 5G || TDD network Deployment \n|}\n\n== Shareholding ==\n\nThe majority owner of Digi Communications NV is RCS Management SA, which includes politicians among shareholders. <ref name=\"ghimpele\">[http://www.ghimpele.ro/2013/06/rcs-rds-ioan-bendei-adevarata-fata-a-conducerii-rcs-rds-oameni-de-afaceri-controversati-si-politicieni-pdl/ Adev\u0103rata fa\u0163\u0103 a conducerii RCS-RDS] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609145426/http://www.ghimpele.ro/2013/06/rcs-rds-ioan-bendei-adevarata-fata-a-conducerii-rcs-rds-oameni-de-afaceri-controversati-si-politicieni-pdl/ |date=2013-06-09 }}</ref> In 2016 the shareholders of this company were:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economie.hotnews.ro/stiri-telecom-21405198-rcs-management-firma-controlata-patronul-rcsrds-zoltan-teszari-vrea-rascumpere-10-din-capital-maxim-22-4-milioane-euro-pana-sfarsitul-acestui.htm |title=RCS Management, firma controlata de patronul RCS&RDS, Zoltan Teszari, vrea sa rascumpere 10% din capital cu maxim 22,4 milioane de euro pana la sfarsitul acestui an |publisher=hotnews.ro |date=9 November 2016}}</ref>\n* Zolt\u00e1n Tesz\u00e1ri \u2013 59.23%\n* Cable Communications Systems NV \u2013 2.47%\n* 8 individual associates \u2013 38.30%\n\n== Constroversy == \n\nIn 2012, the operator removed Discovery channels from the grid, motivating that it would have requested too much money for retransmission. During public discussions, Digi offered to redistribute all Discovery channels in a separate package, but Discovery refused.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.economica.net/rcs-rds-a-scos-joi-seara-toate-canalele-discovery-si-de-pe-retelele-sale-de-cablu_39785.html|title=RCS&RDS a scos toate canalele Discovery \u015fi de pe re\u0163elele sale de cablu |publisher=economica.net |date=29 November 2012}}</ref> Only Discovery and TLC returned to the grid in December 2016.\n\nIn 2012, Digi removed the [[Antena 1 (Romania)|Antena TV Group]] channels from the satellite television grid following disagreements. In 2013, the director of Digi, Ioan Bendei was blackmailed to sign the distribution contract by the director of Antena Group, otherwise he will denounce him for corruption of the television rights of the [[Liga I|national football league]].\nThe director of Antena Group was sentenced to prison for blackmail.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ziare.com/sorin-alexandrescu/rcs-rds/directorul-antenelor-a-santajat-rcs-rds-pentru-un-contract-de-7-2-milioane-de-euro-dna-1238473 |title=Directorul Antenelor a santajat RCS-RDS pentru un contract de 7,2 milioane de euro - DNA |publisher=ziare.com |date=31 May 2013}}</ref>\nAfter evidence of corruption made public by a journalist in 2013, the directors of Digi and of the [[Liga Profesionist\u0103 de Fotbal|Professional Football League]] were convicted in January 2019. <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.grupul.ro/category/r/rcs-rds/ |title=Mitic\u0103 Dragomir \u0219i Ioan Bendei condamna\u021bi la 4 ani de \u00eenchisoare cu executare \u00een dosarul RDS |publisher=grupul.ro |date=16 January 2019}}</ref>\nDigi and Antena Group have dropped the litigations in May 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ziare.com/rcs/rds/dupa-ani-de-zile-de-scandaluri-si-procese-rcs-rds-si-antena-group-au-incheiat-un-contract-prin-care-sting-litigiile-1517941 |title=Dupa ani de zile de scandaluri si procese, RCS&RDS si Antena Group au incheiat un contract prin care sting litigiile |publisher=ziare.com |date=18 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn Hungary, Digi was excluded from the auction for 5G licenses in 2019, motivating its decision on assumptions and facts that are supposed to happen. Digi filed an appeal that was not admitted, then sued NMHH, the regulator of the telecommunications market. Meanwhile, the 5G auction has been closed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://economie.hotnews.ro/stiri-telecom-23764805-grupul-digi-cere-anularea-rezultatelor-licitatiei-5g-din-ungaria-alti-trei-operatori-declarati-castigatori-vor-plati-aproximativ-360-milioane-euro-licente.htm |title=Grupul DIGI cere anularea rezultatelor licita\u021biei 5G din Ungaria: Al\u021bi trei operatori, declara\u021bi c\u00e2\u0219tig\u0103tori, vor pl\u0103ti aproximativ 360 de milioane de euro pe licen\u021be |publisher=hotnews.ro |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|digi-communications.ro}}\n* [http://www.digiromania.ro Digi Romania]\n* [http://www.digi.hu Digi Hungary]\n* [http://www.digimobil.es Digi Spain]\n* [http://www.digimobil.it Digi Italy]\n\n{{CATV Europe}}\n{{Romania mobile phone companies}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Bucharest]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies of Romania]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies of Hungary]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies of Spain]]\n[[Category:Internet service providers of Romania]]\n[[Category:Internet service providers of Spain]]\n[[Category:Mobile phone companies of Romania]]\n[[Category:Mobile phone companies of Spain]]\n[[Category:Mobile phone companies of Italy]]\n[[Category:Cable television companies]]\n[[Category:Romanian television networks]]\n[[Category:Romanian brands]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digi_Communications"}
{"title_page": "Jerry Glanville", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{BLP sources|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name               = Jerry Glanville\n| image              = JerryGlanvilleFeb09.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Glanville in February 2009\n| current_team       = Tampa Bay Vipers\n| position           = [[Defensive coordinator]]\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1941|10|14}}\n| birth_place        = [[Perrysburg, Ohio]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| college            = [[Northern Michigan Wildcats football|Northern Michigan]]\n| pastcoaching       =\n* [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football|Western Kentucky]] (1967)<br>Defensive coordinator\n* [[Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football|Georgia Tech]] (1968\u20131973)<br>Defensive ends/Outside linebackers coach\n* [[Detroit Lions]] ({{NFL Year|1974}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1976}})<br>Defensive assistant/Special teams coordinator\n* [[Atlanta Falcons]] ({{NFL Year|1977}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1978}})<br>Defensive backs coach\n* Atlanta Falcons ({{NFL Year|1979}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1982}})<br>Defensive coordinator\n* [[Buffalo Bills]] ({{NFL Year|1983}})<br>Defensive backs coach\n* [[Houston Oilers]] ({{NFL Year|1984}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1985}})<br>Defensive coordinator\n* Houston Oilers ({{NFL Year|1985}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1989}})<br>Head coach\n* Atlanta Falcons ({{NFL Year|1990}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1993}})<br>Head coach\n* [[Hawaii Warriors football|Hawaii]] (2005\u20132006)<br>Defensive coordinator\n* [[Portland State Vikings football|Portland State]] (2007\u20132009)<br>Head coach\n* [[Hamilton Tiger-Cats]] ({{CFL Year|2018}})<br>Defensive coordinator\n* [[Tampa Bay Vipers]] ({{XFL Year|2020}}\u2013present)<Br>Defensive coordinator\n| regular_record     = {{Winning percentage|60|69|record=y}}\n| playoff_record     = {{Winning percentage|3|4|record=y}}\n| overall_record     = {{Winning percentage|63|73|record=y}} (NFL)<br>{{Winning percentage|9|24|record=y}} (college)\n}}\n'''Jerry Michael Glanville''' (born October 14, 1941) is an [[American football]] coach who is currently the defensive coordinator of the [[Tampa Bay Vipers]] of the [[XFL (2020)|XFL]]. He also played football at [[Northern Michigan University]] in the early 1960s, and is a former [[NASCAR]] driver and owner, and sportscaster. He served as head coach of the [[Houston Oilers]] from 1986 to 1990 and the [[Atlanta Falcons]] from 1990 to 1994, compiling a career [[National Football League|NFL]] record of 63&ndash;73. From 2007 to 2009, he was the Head Football Coach at [[Portland State University]], tallying a mark of 9&ndash;24. Glanville has worked as an analyst on [[HBO]]'s ''[[Inside the NFL]]'', [[CBS Sports|CBS]]'s ''[[The NFL Today]]''/''[[NFL on CBS]]'' and [[Fox Sports (USA)|Fox]]'s coverage of the [[NFL on Fox|NFL]]. He has also raced on the [[Automobile Racing Club of America]] circuit. Glanville also briefly served as a consultant and liaison for the [[United Football League (2009)|United Football League]] in 2011.\n\nWhile head coach of the Houston Oilers, Glanville coined the now-famous phrase \"NFL means 'not for long'\", while admonishing a game official for making what Glanville felt were bad calls. The exact quote is \"This is N-F-L, which stands for 'not for long' when you make them fuckin' calls.\" The \"NFL\" line was in reference to the fact that the official Glanville was criticizing was in his first year in the league, having previously worked in college football.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-videos/09000d5d8213b6cb/Pick-Six-Glanville-NFL-means-Not-For-Long|title=Pick Six: Glanville: 'NFL means 'Not For Long'|work=[[National Football League]]|date=August 5, 2011|accessdate=February 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nGlanville played college football as a middle linebacker at [[Northern Michigan University]], graduating in 1964 with a bachelor's degree. He also holds a master's degree from [[Western Kentucky University]], where he worked as an assistant football coach on campus and roomed with fellow former NFL coach [[Joe Bugel]]. The two were known for drawing football plays on pizza boxes.\n\n==Coaching career==\n\n===National Football League===\nDuring Glanville's time in the [[National Football League]] he was the special teams/defensive assistant for the [[Detroit Lions]] from 1974&ndash;1976, the secondary coach for the [[Atlanta Falcons]] from 1977&ndash;1978 and the Falcons defensive coordinator from 1979\u20131982, the secondary coach of the [[Buffalo Bills]] in 1983, the defensive coordinator of the then [[Houston Oilers]] from 1984\u20131985 and then as head coach from 1985\u20131989 (initially being the interim coach after the firing of [[Hugh Campbell]], and then being the permanent replacement starting in 1986), and head coach of the [[Atlanta Falcons]] from 1990\u20131993.\n\nAs an NFL head coach, Glanville led the Houston Oilers (1985\u20131989) during the era known as the \"House of Pain.\" He was famous for often leaving tickets at will-call for [[Elvis Presley]] (who by that point had been dead for over a decade), wearing all black to be easily recognized by his players, and driving replicas of vehicles driven by actor [[James Dean]]. The Oilers were often chastised for being a dirty, cheap-shot style team, and Glanville often feuded with AFC Central Division rival head coaches [[Sam Wyche]] and [[Marty Schottenheimer]]. He received a highly publicized post-game dressing down from [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] Head Coach [[Chuck Noll]] during the customary postgame handshake after the Oilers defeated the Steelers in the Houston Astrodome during the 1987 season.\n\nGlanville turned the Oilers, a team that had struggled through most of the 1980s, into an aggressive, hard-hitting group that preached a \"hit the beach\" mentality and he made players, such as future Hall of Fame QB [[Warren Moon]], into household names. The Oilers made three playoff appearances during Glanville's tenure (which happened to be during the last three seasons of his tenure), twice playing in the AFC divisional round.  However, his final game with the Oilers was the 1989 AFC Wild Card game, played on December 31, 1989.  Glanville's 1989 squad finished its season with consecutive losses against the Bengals in Cincinnati (61\u20137), at home against the Cleveland Browns in the final seconds in a game that decided the AFC Central title (24\u201320), and at home in the playoffs against the Steelers (26\u201323 in overtime). Had the Oilers defeated Pittsburgh, Glanville would have spent January 6, 1990, preparing the team to play at Denver and, possibly, play for its first AFC Championship Game berth in a decade. Instead, Glanville was fired that day.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1990/01/07/suspense-over-glanville-fired/18a388a3-19be-417d-8db4-7daec9ce760d/</ref> To replace him, Oilers owner K. S. \"Bud\" Adams hired University of Houston head coach and former Redskins and Bears head coach Jack Pardee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1990-01-10-9001030742-story.html|title=PARDEE HIRED TO COACH THE OILERS|first=Don|last=Pierson|date=|website=chicagotribune.com|access-date=April 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nRoughly one week after his firing by the Oilers, Glanville was hired to become the head coach of the Atlanta Falcons (1990\u20131993).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1990-01-14-sp-262-story.html|title=Glanville Has Been Hired to Coach Last-Place Falcons, Paper Reports|author=|date=January 14, 1990|publisher=|access-date=April 10, 2019|via=LA Times}}</ref>  He had been a defensive coordinator for the Falcons, best known for developing the famous \"Gritz Blitz\" defense that featured rushing multiple players on the defensive side of the football against opposing offenses.  The brash Glanville, as well as fan favorites such as cornerback-return specialist Deion Sanders, generated a great deal of excitement in Atlanta.  A perfect preseason in 1990 raised expectations prior to the first game of the season.  The host Falcons withstood a furious rally and scored on a late pick-six by Sanders.  Atlanta defeated Glanville's former team, the Oilers, 47\u201327.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-1990-09-11-1990254072-story.html|title=Falcons' opening win gets Glanville talking Rips Oilers coach Pardee, general manager Holovak, NFL|first=Baltimore|last=Sun|date=|website=baltimoresun.com|access-date=April 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGlanville claimed with Atlanta he inherited a \"flat-tire\" but would take the team to the NFC divisional round in the 1991 season. Season highlights included a season sweep of the 49ers, which cost San Francisco a playoff spot despite both teams finishing 10-6; and the team's first playoff victory since 1978 and only the second playoff win in the franchise's 26-year history.  During his time with the Falcons, the team would pitch a \"Back in Black\" motto with new uniforms and the same aggressive type play on defense, an offensive system known as the \"Red Gun\" that would implement most of the principles associated with the Run-N-Shoot offense, and an emphasis on special teams as he had done in Houston. The Falcons featured talented players such as future Hall of Famer CB \"Prime Time\" [[Deion Sanders]] and were known for unorthodox antics. Expectations were high after the success of the 1991 season and after the Falcons vacated Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium for the Georgia Dome, but the team's consecutive 6\u201310 records for the 1992 and 1993 led the Falcons to dismiss Glanville in 1994. He was out of football until he became the University of Hawaii's defensive coordinator over a decade later. His career record as an NFL head coach is 63\u201373.\n\nWhen Atlanta Falcons general manager Ken Herock selected [[Brett Favre]] in the second round of the [[1991 NFL Draft]], Glanville did not approve of the pick because of Favre's personal issues with [[alcohol (drug)|alcohol]] and the party lifestyle. He said it would take a plane crash for him to put Favre into a game. Glanville also was known to place $100 bets (with Favre and others) on whether or not Favre could throw a football into the third deck of stadiums before games. Glanville claimed the trade in the off-season of 1992 was a wake-up call for Favre who was known for even being late to the team picture during his rookie season with the Falcons.<ref name=\"JSAtlanta\">{{cite web| url=http://www.jsonline.com/story/index.aspx?id=358097 | title=Trading places | last=D'Amato | first=Gary| work=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]| date=October 24, 2005| access-date=February 8, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070603144334/http://www.jsonline.com/story/index.aspx?id=358097 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = June 3, 2007}}</ref> Favre only threw four passes during his one season with Atlanta then was traded to the [[Green Bay Packers]] for a first round pick. Favre went on to play 19 seasons, starting every game from September 20, 1992 to December 5, 2010 and becoming the first NFL player to win three AP MVP awards, as well as the first player to throw for 70,000 passing yards and 500 touchdowns. He would also appear in two Super Bowls, winning [[Super Bowl XXXI]].\n\n===United Football League===\nOn March 21, 2011, the [[Hartford Colonials]] of the [[United Football League (2009)|United Football League]] announced that Glanville would serve as the team's head coach and general manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ufl-football.com/news/jerry-glanville-named-hartford-colonials-head-coach-and-general-manager|title=Jerry Glanville Named Hartford Colonials Head Coach and General Manager|work=United Football League|first=Jerry|last=Glanville|date=March 21, 2011|access-date=March 21, 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110322183003/http://www.ufl-football.com/news/jerry-glanville-named-hartford-colonials-head-coach-and-general-manager|archive-date=March 22, 2011}}</ref> The Colonials suspended operations in August of that year; Glanville would remain with the league as a consultant, color commentator for the league's television broadcasts, and liaison for potential expansion markets. Glanville left the league after one season.\n\n===College football===\n{{Main|Portland State Vikings football under Jerry Glanville}}\nGlanville was formerly the [[defensive coordinator]] for the [[University of Hawaii]]'s football team, working under his former [[offensive coordinator]] (and eventual successor) at Atlanta, [[June Jones]], for two seasons.<ref>{{cite news |title=Glanville figures to upgrade porous defense |first=Len |last=Pasquarelli |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/columns/story?columnist=pasquarelli_len&id=2023672 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=March 28, 2005 |accessdate=March 14, 2011}}</ref> Prior to his tenure at the University of Hawaii, Glanville's earlier involvement with college football was the defensive ends/outside linebackers coach at [[Georgia Institute of Technology|Georgia Tech]] from 1968\u20131973 and the defensive coordinator at [[Western Kentucky University]] in 1967, shortly after his own career as a player had ended.\n\nOn February 28, 2007, Glanville accepted the head coaching position at [[Portland State University]] (PSU), his first college head coaching job.<ref name=GlanvillePDX>{{cite news |title=Jerry Glanville steps down as coach of Portland State Vikings |agency=Associated Press |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=4664290 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=November 17, 2009 |access-date=March 14, 2011}}</ref> Glanville, who replaced [[Tim Walsh (football)|Tim Walsh]], was the program's 12th head coach in their history.  He resigned this position with the support of the university on November 17, 2009, with an overall record of 9\u201324 during his tenure.<ref name=GlanvillePDX/>\n\n===Return to coaching===\nOn February 23, 2018, Glanville was named defensive coordinator for the [[Hamilton Tiger-Cats]] of the [[Canadian Football League]] (CFL).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2018/02/11/jerry-glanville-returns-to-coaching-at-76/|title=Jerry Glanville returns to coaching at 76|first=Mike|last=Florio|date=February 11, 2018|website=nbcsports.com|access-date=April 10, 2019}}</ref> He left the team after the 2018 season for personal reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ticats.ca/tiger-cats-coaching-staff-update/|title=Tiger-Cats Coaching STaff Update|work=[[Hamilton Tiger-Cats]]|date=December 7, 2018|access-date=December 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, he was hired by [[Marc Trestman]] as the defensive coordinator for the [[Tampa Bay Vipers]] of the [[XFL (2020)|XFL]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Parks|first=Greg|url=https://xflboard.com/news/2019/08/05/connecting-the-dots-finding-the-commonalities-among-tampa-bays-coaching-staff-and-with-summer-showcase-players/|title=Connecting the dots: Finding the commonalities among Tampa Bay\u2019s coaching staff, and with Summer Showcase players|publisher=XFL Board|date=August 5, 2019|accessdate=October 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Bassinger|first=Thomas|url=https://www.tampabay.com/sports/bucs/2019/06/03/tampa-bay-xfl-team-hires-former-usf-executive-josh-bullock-as-its-president/|title=Tampa Bay XFL team hires former USF executive Josh Bullock as its president|newspaper=[[Tampa Bay Times]]|date=June 3, 2019|accessdate=October 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Racing career==\n{{Infobox NASCAR driver\n|Total_Busch_Races  = 6\n|Years_In_Busch     = 2\n|Best_Busch_Pos     = 65th ([[1992 NASCAR Busch Series|1992]])\n|First_Busch_Race   = [[1992 NASCAR Busch Series|1992]] [[Roses Stores 300]] ([[Orange County Speedway|Orange County]])\n|Last_Busch_Race    = [[1993 NASCAR Busch Series|1993]] [[Havoline 250]] ([[Milwaukee Mile|Milwaukee]])\n|Busch_Wins         = 0\n|Busch_Top_Tens     = 0\n|Busch_Poles        = 0\n|Total_Truck_Races  = 27\n|Years_In_Truck     = 5\n|Best_Truck_Pos     = 18th ([[1995 NASCAR SuperTruck Series|1995]])\n|First_Truck_Race   = [[1995 NASCAR SuperTruck Series|1995]] [[1995 Skoal Bandit Copper World Classic|Skoal Bandit Copper World Classic]] ([[Phoenix International Raceway|Phoenix]])\n|Last_Truck_Race    = [[1999 NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series|1999]] [[F.W. Webb 175|Pennzoil/VIP Discount Auto Center 200]] ([[New Hampshire Motor Speedway|Loudon]])\n|Truck_Wins         = 0\n|Truck_Top_Tens     = 0\n|Truck_Poles        = 0\n}}\nGlanville began racing by learning from seven-time [[Winston Cup Series]] champion [[Dale Earnhardt]], who would mentor Glanville in tests at [[Richmond International Raceway]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Smith|first=Marty|url=http://espn.go.com/racing/nascar/cup/story/_/id/8135950/nascar-door-door-jerry-glanville-professor-earnhardt|title=Jerry Glanville tells tales of Big E|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=July 6, 2012|accessdate=October 30, 2015}}</ref> Glanville officially started his racing career in the [[NASCAR]] [[Busch Grand National Series]] in [[1992 NASCAR Busch Series|1992]] for Lewis Cooper with sponsorship from the Falcons. After failing to qualify in his first career attempt at [[Lanier Speedway]], he made his series debut at [[Orange County Speedway]], finishing 22nd.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.racing-reference.info/drivdet/glanvje01/1992/B|title=1992 NASCAR Busch Grand National Series Results|work=Racing-Reference|accessdate=October 30, 2015}}</ref> He ran six races during his three-year timespan in the series, with a best finish of 20th at [[Volusia County Speedway]] in 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.racing-reference.info/race/1992_X-1R_Firecracker_200/B|title=1992 X-1R Firecracker 200|work=Racing-Reference|accessdate=October 30, 2015}}</ref> Glanville returned to the series in [[1999 NASCAR Busch Series|1999]], but failed to qualify for all five races he attempted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.racing-reference.info/drivdet/glanvje01/1999/B|title=1999 NASCAR Busch Grand National Series Results|work=Racing-Reference|accessdate=October 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe later ran in the [[ARCA Hooters SuperCar Series]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Pockrass |first=Bob |url=http://www.sportingnews.com/nascar/story/2013-01-31/super-bowl-2013-nfl-dan-marino-randy-moss-brett-favre-troy-aikman-joe-gibbs |title=NFL and NASCAR: Former NFL stars who dabbled in stock-car racing |work=[[Sporting News]] |date=January 31, 2014 |access-date=March 2, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130522121301/http://www.sportingnews.com/nascar/story/2013-01-31/super-bowl-2013-nfl-dan-marino-randy-moss-brett-favre-troy-aikman-joe-gibbs |archivedate=May 22, 2013 }}</ref> running ten races in 1994 as an [[Owner-Driver (NASCAR)|owner/driver]] of the No. 81, and recorded a best finish of ninth at [[I-70 Speedway]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.racing-reference.info/drivdet/glanvje01/1994/A|title=1994 ARCA Hooters SuperCar Series Results|work=Racing-Reference|access-date=October 30, 2015}}</ref> Glanville returned to ARCA in 2000, running a part-time schedule until 2004 for his and [[Norm Benning]]'s teams, his best finish being fourth at [[Nashville Superspeedway]] in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.racing-reference.info/rquery?id=glanvje01&trk=t0&series=A|title=ARCA Racing Series Results (races)|work=Racing-Reference|access-date=October 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, he participated in the [[1995 Skoal Bandit Copper World Classic|Skoal Bandit Copper World Classic]], the inaugural [[SuperTruck Series]] race,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popularspeed.com/remember-when-mike-skinner-and-the-truck-series-arrives/|title=Remember When: Mike Skinner and the Truck Series Arrives|work=Popular Speed|date=July 30, 2014|accessdate=October 27, 2015}}</ref> and finished 27th.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.racing-reference.info/race/1995_Skoal_Bandit_Copper_World_Classic/C|title=1995 Skoal Bandit Copper World Classic|work=Racing-Reference|accessdate=October 26, 2015}}</ref> He continued racing in the Truck Series from 1995\u20131999, with a best finish of 14th three times.\n\nIn addition to the Busch and Truck Series, Glanville competed in the NASCAR [[Slim Jim All Pro Series]] in 1996, finishing 23rd at [[Gresham Motorsports Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.racing-reference.info/race/1996_BellSouth_Mobility_200/SE|title=1996 BellSouth Mobility 200|work=Racing-Reference|accessdate=October 30, 2015}}</ref> He later raced in the [[Winston West Series]], his debut coming in 1997 at [[Pikes Peak International Raceway]], where he finished seventh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.racing-reference.info/race/1997_NASCAR_500K/P|title=1997 NASCAR 500K|work=Racing-Reference|accessdate=October 30, 2015}}</ref> From 1997\u20131999, he ran eight races in the [[Hooters Pro Cup]], with a best finish of 12th at [[Southampton Speedway]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.racing-reference.info/rquery?id=glanvje01&trk=t0&series=US|title=X-1R Pro Cup Series Results (races)|work=Racing-Reference|accessdate=October 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\nGlanville was also working for [[CBS Sports]] during this period, mainly as an [[The NFL Today|NFL studio]] analyst. Glanville also called several NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series races on [[NASCAR on CBS|CBS]]/[[NASCAR on TNN|TNN]] during this period, mainly as a race analyst in the booth.\n\n==In media==\nThe [[Sega Genesis]] system offered ''Jerry Glanville's PigSkin Footbrawl'', a [[medieval]]-themed arcade-style football game. The game was a port of the 1990 classic arcade game ''[[Pigskin 621 A.D.]]'', released by [[Midway Games|Bally Midway]]. Glanville provided soundbites for the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://retrovolve.com/jerry-glanvilles-pigskin-footbrawl-brought-hyper-violent-football-to-the-genesis-in-1992/|title=Jerry Glanville\u2019s Pigskin Footbrawl Brought Hyper-Violent Football to the Genesis in 1992}}</ref>\n\n==Head coaching record==\n\n===National Football League===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Team !!rowspan=2|Year !! colspan=\"5\"|Regular Season !! colspan=\"4\"|Post Season\n|-\n!Won !!Lost!!Ties!!Win %!!Finish!!Won!!Lost!!Win %!!Result\n|-\n![[1985 Houston Oilers season|HOU]]||[[1985 NFL season|1985]]\n|0||2||0||.000||4th in AFC Central || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013\n|-\n![[1986 Houston Oilers season|HOU]]||[[1986 NFL season|1986]]\n|5||11||0||.313||4th in AFC Central || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013\n|- style=\"background:#fdd;\"\n![[1987 Houston Oilers season|HOU]]||[[1987 NFL season|1987]]\n|9||6||0||.600||2nd in AFC Central|| 1  || 1  || .500  || <small>'''Lost to [[Denver Broncos]] in [[1987\u201388 NFL playoffs|Divisional Playoff]].'''</small>\n|- style=\"background:#fdd;\"\n![[1988 Houston Oilers season|HOU]]||[[1988 NFL season|1988]]\n|10||6||0||.625||3rd in AFC Central|| 1  || 1  || .500  || <small>'''Lost to [[Buffalo Bills]] in [[1988\u201389 NFL playoffs|Divisional Playoff]].'''</small>\n|- style=\"background:#fdd;\"\n![[1989 Houston Oilers season|HOU]]||[[1989 NFL season|1989]]\n|9||7||0||.563||2nd in AFC Central|| 0  || 1  || .000  || <small>'''Lost to [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] in [[1989\u201390 NFL playoffs|Wildcard Game]].'''</small>\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|HOU Total||33||32||0||.508||||2||3||.400||\n|-\n![[1990 Atlanta Falcons season|ATL]]||[[1990 NFL season|1990]]\n|5||11||0||.313||4th in NFC West||\u2013||\u2013||\u2013||\n|- style=\"background:#fdd;\"\n![[1991 Atlanta Falcons season|ATL]]||[[1991 NFL season|1991]]\n|10||6||0||.625||2nd in NFC West|| 1  || 1  || .500  ||<small>'''Lost to [[Washington Redskins]] in [[1991\u201392 NFL playoffs|Divisional Playoff]].'''</small>\n|-\n![[1992 Atlanta Falcons season|ATL]]||[[1992 NFL season|1992]]\n|6||10||0||.375||3rd in NFC West||\u2013||\u2013||\u2013||\n|-\n![[1993 Atlanta Falcons season|ATL]]||[[1993 NFL season|1993]]\n|6||10||0||.375||3rd in NFC West||\u2013||\u2013